{"title_page": "Felipe Alaiz", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=November 2019}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{short description|Spanish writer and  journalist}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Felipe Alaiz\n| image        =Felipe Alaiz.jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| smallimage   =\n| caption      =\n| order        =\n| office1      = Member of League of Human Rights - France\n| term_start1  = \n| predecessor1 =  \n| successor1   =\n| term_start2  = \n| term_end2    = \n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2   = \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = 23 May 1887\n| birth_place  = [[Belver de Cinca]] ([[Spain]])\n| death_date   = 8 April 1959\n| death_place  = [[Paris]] ([[France]])\n| nationality  =\n| party        = \n| spouse       = \n| relations    =\n| children     = \n| Education    = \n| alma_mater   =\n| occupation   = writer\n| profession   = Human right activist <br/> Politician\n| religion     = \n| website      =\n| footnotes    =\n}}\n'''Felipe Alaiz de Pablo''' ,  born on 23 May 1887 at [[Belver de Cinca]] ( [[province of Huesca]]  ) and died on 8 April 1959 in [[Paris]] . He was  a [[Spain|Spanish]] writer, translator and  journalist of the [[libertarian movement]].<ref>\u00ab\u00a0Felipe Ala\u00edz (1887\u20131959), une des plumes les plus brillantes du mouvement libertaire espagnol \u00bb, Paolo Gobetti, ''Un entretien avec [[Jos\u00e9 Peirats]] (juin 1976)'', \u00c0 contretemps, n\u00b0 25, janvier 2007, [http://acontretemps.org/spip.php?article140#nb10 note 10].</ref> He is considered to be the first openly Spanish [[anarchist]]  writer.<ref>Data [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France|BNF]] : [http://data.bnf.fr/10879821/felipe_alaiz/ Felipe Alaiz (1887\u20131959)].</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nFelipe Alaiz studied in [[Lleida]], Huesca and [[Zaragoza]].  For two years he was the editor of magazine La Revista de Arag\u00f3n (Zaragoza, 1914). At a very young age, Felipe Alaiz devoted himself to militant journalism, an activity he followed all his life. He was a professor of literature at Liceo Escolar de L\u00e9rida, an avant-garde educational center founded by Federico God\u00e0s Legido. That was where he met other young teachers such as [[Joaqu\u00edn Maur\u00edn]] and V\u00edctor Colomer.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Spanish anarchists]]\n[[Category:Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional del Trabajo members]]\n[[Category:Anarcho-syndicalists]]\n[[Category:Spanish trade unionists]]\n[[Category:Spanish journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century writers]]\n[[Category:Exiles of the Spanish Civil War]]\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:1959 deaths]]\n\n\n{{Spain-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=November 2019}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{short description|Spanish writer and  journalist}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Felipe Alaiz\n| image        =Felipe Alaiz.jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| smallimage   =\n| caption      =\n| order        =\n| office1      = Member of League of Human righs - France\n| term_start1  = \n| predecessor1 =  \n| successor1   =\n| term_start2  = \n| term_end2    = \n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2   = \n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = 23 May 1887\n| birth_place  = [[Belver de Cinca]] ([[Spain]])\n| death_date   = 8 April 1959\n| death_place  = [[Paris]] ([[France]])\n| nationality  =\n| party        = \n| spouse       = \n| relations    =\n| children     = \n| Education    = \n| alma_mater   =\n| occupation   = writer\n| profession   = Human right activist <br/> Politician\n| religion     = \n| website      =\n| footnotes    =\n}}\n'''Felipe Alaiz de Pablo''' ,  born on 23 May 1887 at [[Belver de Cinca]] ( [[province of Huesca]]  ) and died on 8 April 1959 in [[Paris]] . He was  a [[Spain|Spanish]] writer, translator and  journalist of the [[libertarian movement]].<ref>\u00ab\u00a0Felipe Ala\u00edz (1887\u20131959), une des plumes les plus brillantes du mouvement libertaire espagnol \u00bb, Paolo Gobetti, ''Un entretien avec [[Jos\u00e9 Peirats]] (juin 1976)'', \u00c0 contretemps, n\u00b0 25, janvier 2007, [http://acontretemps.org/spip.php?article140#nb10 note 10].</ref> He is considered to be the first openly Spanish [[anarchist]]  writer.<ref>Data [[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France|BNF]] : [http://data.bnf.fr/10879821/felipe_alaiz/ Felipe Alaiz (1887\u20131959)].</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\nFelipe Alaiz studied in [[Lleida]], Huesca and [[Zaragoza]].  For two years he was the editor of magazine La Revista de Arag\u00f3n (Zaragoza, 1914). At a very young age, Felipe Alaiz devoted himself to militant journalism, an activity he followed all his life. He was a professor of literature at Liceo Escolar de L\u00e9rida, an avant-garde educational center founded by Federico God\u00e0s Legido. That was where he met other young teachers such as [[Joaqu\u00edn Maur\u00edn]] and V\u00edctor Colomer.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Spanish anarchists]]\n[[Category:Confederaci\u00f3n Nacional del Trabajo members]]\n[[Category:Anarcho-syndicalists]]\n[[Category:Spanish trade unionists]]\n[[Category:Spanish journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century writers]]\n[[Category:Exiles of the Spanish Civil War]]\n[[Category:1887 births]]\n[[Category:1959 deaths]]\n\n\n{{Spain-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Felipe_Alaiz"}
