ing both Coachella and Stagecoach to October due to health concerns over the coronavirus pandemic. The promoter made the decision \"at the direction of the County of Riverside and local health authorities\". The new dates for Coachella 2020 are October 9\u201311 and October 16\u201318.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/music/story/2020-03-10/coachella-rescheduled-postponed-stagecoach-october|title=It's official: Coachella has been postponed until October|date=March 10, 2020|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/10/entertainment/coachella-postponed-coronavirus/index.html|title=Coachella, Stagecoach officially postponed over coronavirus concerns|first1=Chloe |last1=Melas |first2=Sandra|last2=Gonzalez|website=CNN|access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"lat_canc\">{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-03-12/events-canceled-postponed-coronavirus|title=Here are events canceled or postponed due to coronavirus|website=Los Angeles Times|date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[California Interscholastic Federation|CIF]] [[California high school basketball championship|state basketball championships]] were cancelled<ref name=\"lat_canc\" />\n* USC spring football was cancelled<ref name=\"lat_canc\" />\n* The Los Angeles Philharmonic, Los Angeles Opera and Center Theatre Group cancelled performances and festivals<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/story/2020-03-12/coronavirus-closures-la-phil-la-opera|title=Coronavirus cancellations hit L.A. Phil, L.A. Opera and Center Theatre Group|date=March 12, 2020|website=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n* [[Electronic Entertainment Expo]] 2020 (E3) was cancelled<ref name=\"lat_canc\" />\n* [[RuPaul's DragCon LA]] 2020 was cancelled<ref name=\"lat_canc\" />\n* The [[Game Developers Conference|Game Developers' Conference (GDC)]] in San Francisco, originally scheduled for March 16\u201320, was postponed to summer<ref name=\"lat_canc\" />\n* Google Cloud Next '20 was converted to online format<ref name=\"lat_canc\" />\n* The [[Facebook F8]] Conference was converted to online format<ref name=\"lat_canc\" />\n* [[Google I/O]], originally May 12\u201314, cancelled<ref name=\"lat_canc\" />\n* The [[Indian Wells Masters]] tennis tournament has been cancelled for this year.<ref name=\"iw\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/09/tennis/indian-wells-coronavirus-cancellation-tennis-spt-intl/index.html|title=Coronavirus forces cancellation of Indian Wells|website=CNN}}</ref>\n* [[WonderCon]] was postponed.<ref>{{cite news |last=McMillan |first=Graeme |date=12 March 2020 |title=WonderCon Anaheim Postponed Due to Coronavirus |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/wondercon-anaheim-postponed-due-coronavirus-1284340 |work=The Hollywood Reporter |access-date=16 March 2020 }}</ref>\n* [[BottleRock Napa Valley]] 2020 was postponed to October 2\u20134.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vaziri |first1=Aidin |title=BottleRock 2020 festival postponed due to coronavirus outbreak |url=https://datebook.sfchronicle.com/music/bottlerock-2020-festival-postponed-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak |department=Datebook |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |date=2020-03-18}}</ref>\n* [[Bay to Breakers]] 2020 was postponed to September 20.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abc7news.com/5990803/|title=Coronavirus Impact: Cancellations, closures related to COVID-19 in San Francisco Bay Area|website=ABC7 News|date=2020-03-21}}</ref>\n\n==Effects on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nMost of state's sports teams were affected. In [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]] on March 12, and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Los Angeles Dodgers season|Los Angeles Dodgers]], [[2020 Los Angeles Angels season|Los Angeles Angels]], [[2020 San Francisco Giants season|San Francisco Giants]], [[2020 Oakland Athletics season|Oakland Athletics]], and [[2020 San Diego Padres season|San Diego Padres]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>  In the [[National Basketball Association]], the season was suspended for 30 days starting on March 12, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Los Angeles Lakers season|Los Angeles Lakers]], [[2019\u201320 Los Angeles Clippers season|Los Angeles Clippers]], [[2019\u201320 Sacramento Kings season|Sacramento Kings]], and [[2019\u201320 Golden State Warriors season|Golden State Warriors]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28893331/nba-owners-seeking-30-day-reevaluation-suspension-games |title=Silver: NBA hiatus likely to last 'at least' 30 days |date=March 12, 2020 |website=ESPN.com |language=en|access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Also on March 12, the [[National Hockey League]] suspended the season indefinitely, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Los Angeles Kings season|Los Angeles Kings]], [[2019\u201320 Anaheim Ducks season|Anaheim Ducks]], and [[2019\u201320 San Jose Sharks season|San Jose Sharks]].<ref>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] NHL, March 12, 2020</ref> The [[Major League Soccer]] season was suspended for 30 days starting on March 12, affecting the [[2020 LA Galaxy season|LA Galaxy]], [[2020 Los Angeles FC season|Los Angeles FC]], and [[2020 San Jose Earthquakes season|San Jose Earthquakes]].<ref>[https://www.espn.com/soccer/major-league-soccer/story/4073255/mls-postponed-for-30-days-usmnt-uswnt-friendlies-canceled MLS postponed for 30 days; USMNT, USWNT friendlies canceled] ESPN, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nAlso on March 12, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\nAt the high school level, the [[California Interscholastic Federation]], or CIF, canceled the basketball state championship tournament after the Northern California and Southern California semifinals.  During the tournament, 3 schools including [[Sheldon High School (California)|Sheldon]],[[Archbishop Riordan High School| \nArchbishop Riordan]], and the [[Menlo School]] withdrew from the tournament after their schools were shut down. Currently, spring sports for high schools have all been postponed until at least April 7. The CIF will be reevaluating and giving a further directive on April 3.  This includes the sports of baseball, softball, badminton, track and field, swimming, boys golf and boys tennis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cifstate.org/landing/index|title=California Interscholastic Federation|website=www.cifstate.org}}</ref>\n\n==Effects on prisons==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on prisons}}\n\n* '''Alameda County:''' On March 20, Alameda County officials announced that 247 people would be released from Santa Rita Jail, located in Dublin.<ref name=lat>Marua Dolan, Alene Tchekmedyian, Piage St. John, [https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-03-20/california-releases-more-jail-inmates-amid-coronavirus-crisis \"California releases more jail inmates amid coronavirus crisis,\"] Los Angeles Times, March 20, 2020</ref>\n* '''San Diego County:''' On March 16, the Sheriff's Department said it had started reducing the number of people being accepted into the county's seven jails and had received approval for early release of some prisoners. Other measures included in-cell meals, a suspension of visitation, and suspension of jail programs.<ref>Teri Figueroa, Karen Kucher, [https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/public-safety/story/2020-03-16/jails-to-release-some-inmates-adjust-booking-criteria-amid-coronavirus-concerns \"Jails to release some inmates, adjust booking criteria amid coronavirus concerns,\"] San Diego Union-Tribune, March 16, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Effects on religion==\n{{main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion}}\n\nOn March 13, the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of San Jose in California]] closed all diocesan schools from until at least April 20. It suspended public Masses and [[Dispensation (canon law)|dispense]]d with the obligation to attend Mass from March 14 until further notice.<ref>{{cite web|title=Coronavirus (COVID-19)|publisher=Roman Catholic Diocese of San Jose in California|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url=https://www.dsj.org/coronavirus/}}</ref> On March 18, the California Catholic Conference of bishops followed suit, suspending the public celebration of Mass throughout the state until further notice.<ref>{{cite press release|title=Public Celebration of Mass Suspended throughout California|publisher=California Catholic Conference|date=March 18, 2020|accessdate=March 22, 2020|url=https://www.cacatholic.org/mass-suspension}}</ref> Many churches are conducting services online during the time of closure.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nChurches and synagogues with more than 30 members officially closed doors March 12. Most began streaming via YouTube, Facebook and etc. When the quarantine officially began, all congregations were no longer able to gather. Most are holding weekly prayer meetings as well as Saturday or Sunday morning streaming of worship services.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nMosques in California have stopped holding Friday prayer congregations.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n* [[Travel restrictions related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/OPA/Pages/Office-of-Public-Affairs.aspx California CDPH Office of Public Affairs], news releases by [[California Department of Public Health]] (CDPH)\n* [https://www.gov.ca.gov/2020/03/12/governor-newsom-issues-new-executive-order-further-enhancing-state-and-local-governments-ability-to-respond-to-covid-19-pandemic/ Governor Newsom Issues New Executive Order Further Enhancing State and Local Government's Ability to Respond to COVID-19 Pandemic (March 12, 2020)] \u2013 Cancel large gatherings more than 250 people\n* [https://www.sccgov.org/sites/phd/DiseaseInformation/novel-coronavirus/Pages/dashboard.aspx Santa Clara County Coronavirus (COVID-19) Data Dashboard]\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|California]]\n[[Category:2020 in California|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in California]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Health in California]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "name_user": "Victory in Germany", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSouthern California", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_California"}
{"title_page": "D-Girl (The Sopranos)", "text_new": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:D-Girl (''The Sopranos'')}}\n{{Infobox television episode\n| title          = D-Girl\n| series         = [[The Sopranos]]\n| image          = Sopranos D-Girl.jpg\n| caption        = A scene on the set of [[Jon Favreau]]'s new movie, to which Christopher is invited to visit.\n| season         = 2\n| episode        = 7\n| guests         = ''see below''\n| airdate        = February 27, 2000\n| length         = 56 minutes\n| editor         = \n| production     = 207\n| writer         = [[Todd A. Kessler]]\n| director       = [[Allen Coulter]]\n| photographer   = [[Phil Abraham]]\n| episode_list   = List of The Sopranos episodes\n| season_article = The Sopranos (season 2)\n| prev           = [[The Happy Wanderer (The Sopranos)|The Happy Wanderer]]\n| next           = [[Full Leather Jacket]]\n}}\n\n\"'''D-Girl'''\" is the 20th episode of the [[HBO]] original series ''[[The Sopranos]]'' and the seventh of the show's second season. It was written by [[Todd A. Kessler]] and directed by [[Allen Coulter]], and originally aired on February 27, 2000.\n\n==Starring==\n* [[James Gandolfini]] as [[Tony Soprano]]\n* [[Lorraine Bracco]] as [[Dr. Jennifer Melfi]]\n* [[Edie Falco]] as [[Carmela Soprano]]\n* [[Michael Imperioli]] as [[Christopher Moltisanti]]\n* [[Dominic Chianese]] as [[Junior Soprano|Corrado Soprano, Jr.]]*\n* [[Vincent Pastore]] as [[Pussy Bonpensiero]]\n* [[Steven Van Zandt]] as [[Silvio Dante]] *\n* [[Tony Sirico]] as [[Paulie Gualtieri]] *\n* [[Robert Iler]] as [[Anthony Soprano, Jr.]]\n* [[Jamie-Lynn Sigler]] as [[Meadow Soprano]]\n* [[Drea de Matteo]] as [[Adriana La Cerva]]\n* [[David Proval]] as [[Richie Aprile]]\n* [[Aida Turturro]] as [[Janice Soprano]]\n* [[Nancy Marchand]] as [[Livia Soprano]]\n\n''* = credit only''\n\n===Guest starring===\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Jon Favreau]] as himself\n* [[Sandra Bernhard]] as herself\n* [[Janeane Garofalo]] as herself\n* [[Alicia Witt]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Amy Safir|Amy Safir]]\n* [[Louis Lombardi|Louis Lombardi, Jr.]] as [[FBI on The Sopranos#Agent Skip Lipari|Skip Lipari]]\n* [[Toni Kalem]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Angie Bonpensiero|Angie Bonpensiero]]\n* Arthur Barnes as Security Guard\n* [[Stephen Bienskie]] as Hotel Clerk\n* John Devlin as Assistant Director\n* [[Dominic Fumusa]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Gregory Moltisanti|Gregory Moltisanti]]\n* [[Andersen Gabrych]] as UTA Receptionist\n* [[Bryan Matzkow]] as Hotel Manager\n* [[Andrea Maulella]] as Michele Forman\n* Jason Minter as Bellman\n* [[Frank Pando]] as [[FBI on The Sopranos#Agent Frank Grasso|Agent Grasso]]\n* [[Steve Porcelli]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Matt Bonpensiero|Matt Bonpensiero]]\n* [[Elizabeth Reaser]] as Stace\n* [[Asa Somers]] as Blaine Richardson\n}}\n\n==Synopsis==\n[[Christopher Moltisanti|Christopher]] and [[Adriana La Cerva|Adriana]] meet his cousin [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Gregory Moltisanti|Greg]] and his fianc\u00e9e [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Amy Safir|Amy Safir]]. Amy works for [[Jon Favreau]], and they are filming in New York. She has been eager to meet Christopher and read his screenplay; as she says, mob-themed stories are a hit. She is also struck by Christopher as a man. At home, Adriana tells Chris she has kept a copy of the screenplay he threw away, and persuades him to pass it to Jon and Amy. Both Chris and Adriana have been invited to the film set, but he goes alone. He is absorbed by what he sees, and makes a suggestion Jon gratefully adopts.\n\nJon wants to learn from Chris about mob customs and speech. When Chris comes as arranged to his hotel room he is not available, so he calls on Amy instead. They talk, she begins to give him advice about writing a screenplay, and they have sex. Another day, he manages to catch her in the hotel lobby and they go to her room again for sex, but afterwards she is overcome by guilt. In her room Chris finds a screenplay by Jon and sees that he has stolen a mob anecdote that Chris told him in confidence. Furious, Chris searches for him, but he has returned to California. In the following days, Amy does not reply to his messages. He finally tracks her down. She tells him, \"It was wrong, with us,\" and that, for the time being, [[Hollywood]] has lost interest in mob films. She turns her back on him. \n\n[[Anthony Soprano, Jr.|A.J.]] takes [[Carmela Soprano|his mother]]'s car without permission and damages it. When his parents rebuke him he baffles them by stating that life is absurd, and he does not wish to be  [[confirmation|confirmed]] because there is no God. [[Tony Soprano|Tony]] consults [[Big Pussy Bonpensiero|Pussy]], who is A.J.'s [[Godparent|godfather]] and confirmation sponsor; Pussy says that at that age \"they get broody.\" Tony consults [[Jennifer Melfi|Dr. Melfi]], who explains that A.J. has discovered [[existentialist|existentialism]]. A.J. consults [[Livia Soprano|his grandmother]] who tells him not to expect happiness; everyone dies alone; \"It's all a big nothing.\"\n\nPussy is forced by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] to wear a [[Covert listening device|wire]] at A.J.'s confirmation and the ensuing reception at the Soprano home. During the reception, Tony discovers A.J. and two friends smoking [[marijuana]] in the garage. Pussy goes up to A.J.'s room, where he is sulking, and gently tells him that his father is a good man; A.J. is young and should enjoy life. He hugs him and sends him back down to the party, but Pussy himself goes into the toilet and sobs.    \n\nAdriana has inadvertently told Tony about the screenplay-writing. Chris misses the confirmation ceremony and arrives late for the reception. Tony then tells him he has a choice: either to follow his other interests, or to completely commit himself to him. Chris goes out and thinks it over, then goes back to Tony.<ref name=\"HBOepisode\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.hbo.com/the-sopranos/episodes#/the-sopranos/episodes/2/20-d-girl/synopsis.html\n|title=HBO: The Sopranos: S 2 EP 20 D-Girl: Synopsis\n|publisher=[[HBO]]\n|accessdate=2014-03-03}}</ref><ref name=\"The Sopranos: Episode Guide\">{{cite book\n|title=The Sopranos: The Complete Book\n|last1=O'Connor\n|first1=Mimi\n|editor1-last=Martin\n|editor1-first=Brett\n|date=2007-10-30\n|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]]\n|location=[[New York City|New York]]\n|isbn=978-1-933821-18-4\n|chapter=''The Sopranos'': Episode Guide\n|page=225}}</ref>\n\n==Title reference==\nThe episode's title is a shortened title for \"[[development girl]]\", used mostly in the film and television industry.\n\n==Cultural references==\n* Christopher refers to the comedy film ''[[The Gang That Couldn't Shoot Straight (film)]]'' (1971) when Favreau talks about his passion to make and star in another film about \"Crazy [[Joe Gallo]].\"\n* Amy reminds Christopher that ''[[Mickey Blue Eyes]]'' (which starred [[Vincent Pastore]]) is an example of another mob movie that failed to live up to its advance billing.\n* Adriana tells Amy and John that she enjoyed Favreau's film ''[[Swingers (1996 film)|Swingers]]'' (1996), with [[Vince Vaughn]].\n* When Carmela and Tony express concern about AJ's existentialist pronouncements, Meadow quotes [[Germaine de Sta\u00ebl|Mme de Sta\u00ebl]]:  \"One must choose in life between boredom and suffering.\u201d\n* Meadow says that A.J. has been assigned [[The_Stranger_(Camus_novel)|The Stranger]], a novel by Albert Camus. \n* When Christopher relates the story of the trans woman whose lover threw acid in her face after becoming intimate and learning that she was actually transsexual, Amy recalls the film, ''[[The Crying Game]]'' (1992).\n* Amy relates [[Maslow's hierarchy of needs]] to Christopher before becoming intimate with him.\n* When Amy tells Christopher they were wrong to have begun a relationship and Christopher responds that he really liked her, Amy observes that the mood has become rather \"[[William Inge]]\".\n\n== Music ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=September 2017}}\n* The song played over the end credits is \"Vedi, Maria\", by [[Emma Shapplin]].\n* When Chris, John, and Amy sit down at the pizza shop, the song played is \"[[Swingtown (song)|Swingtown]]\" by the [[Steve Miller Band]]. It is then followed by \"[[Rhiannon (song)|Rhiannon]]\" by [[Fleetwood Mac]].\n* Other music included in this episode includes \"Tasty Pudding\" by [[Chet Baker]], \"Shaolin Satellite\" by [[Thievery Corporation]], \"Voulez-Vous?\" by [[Arling & Cameron]], and \"Caught My Mind\" by [[Pushmonkey]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hbo.com/the-sopranos/episodes/index.html#/the-sopranos/episodes/2/20-d-girl/index.html \"D-Girl\"] at [[HBO]]\n*{{imdb episode|0705238|D-Girl}}\n*{{tv.com episode|the-sopranos/d-girl-26467|D-Girl}}\n\n{{The Sopranos}}\n\n[[Category:The Sopranos (season 2) episodes]]\n[[Category:2000 American television episodes]]\n\n[[fr:La Garce (Les Soprano)]]\n", "text_old": "{{DISPLAYTITLE:D-Girl (''The Sopranos'')}}\n{{Infobox television episode \n| title = D-Girl\n| series = [[The Sopranos]]\n| image = Sopranos D-Girl.jpg\n| caption  = \n| season = 2\n| episode = 7\n| guests= ''see below''\n| airdate = February 27, 2000\n| length = 56 minutes\n| production = 207\n| writer = [[Todd A. Kessler]]\n| director = [[Allen Coulter]]\n| photographer = [[Phil Abraham]]\n| episode_list = List of The Sopranos episodes\n| season_article = The Sopranos (season 2)\n| prev = [[The Happy Wanderer (The Sopranos)|The Happy Wanderer]]\n| next = [[Full Leather Jacket]]\n}}\n\n\"'''D-Girl'''\" is the 20th episode of the [[HBO]] original series ''[[The Sopranos]]'' and the seventh of the show's second season. It was written by [[Todd A. Kessler]] and directed by [[Allen Coulter]], and originally aired on February 27, 2000.\n\n==Starring==\n* [[James Gandolfini]] as [[Tony Soprano]]\n* [[Lorraine Bracco]] as [[Dr. Jennifer Melfi]]\n* [[Edie Falco]] as [[Carmela Soprano]]\n* [[Michael Imperioli]] as [[Christopher Moltisanti]]\n* [[Dominic Chianese]] as [[Junior Soprano|Corrado Soprano, Jr.]]*\n* [[Vincent Pastore]] as [[Pussy Bonpensiero]]\n* [[Steven Van Zandt]] as [[Silvio Dante]] *\n* [[Tony Sirico]] as [[Paulie Gualtieri]] *\n* [[Robert Iler]] as [[Anthony Soprano, Jr.]]\n* [[Jamie-Lynn Sigler]] as [[Meadow Soprano]]\n* [[Drea de Matteo]] as [[Adriana La Cerva]]\n* [[David Proval]] as [[Richie Aprile]]\n* [[Aida Turturro]] as [[Janice Soprano]]\n* [[Nancy Marchand]] as [[Livia Soprano]]\n\n''* = credit only''\n\n===Guest starring===\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n* [[Jon Favreau]] as himself\n* [[Sandra Bernhard]] as herself\n* [[Janeane Garofalo]] as herself\n* [[Alicia Witt]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Amy Safir|Amy Safir]]\n* [[Louis Lombardi|Louis Lombardi, Jr.]] as [[FBI on The Sopranos#Agent Skip Lipari|Skip Lipari]]\n* [[Toni Kalem]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Angie Bonpensiero|Angie Bonpensiero]]\n* Arthur Barnes as Security Guard\n* [[Stephen Bienskie]] as Hotel Clerk\n* John Devlin as Assistant Director\n* [[Dominic Fumusa]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Gregory Moltisanti|Gregory Moltisanti]]\n* [[Andersen Gabrych]] as UTA Receptionist\n* [[Bryan Matzkow]] as Hotel Manager\n* [[Andrea Maulella]] as Michele Forman\n* Jason Minter as Bellman\n* [[Frank Pando]] as [[FBI on The Sopranos#Agent Frank Grasso|Agent Grasso]]\n* [[Steve Porcelli]] as [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Matt Bonpensiero|Matt Bonpensiero]]\n* [[Elizabeth Reaser]] as Stace\n* [[Asa Somers]] as Blaine Richardson\n}}\n\n==Synopsis==\n[[Christopher Moltisanti|Christopher]] and [[Adriana La Cerva|Adriana]] meet his cousin [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Gregory Moltisanti|Greg]] and his fianc\u00e9e [[List of characters from The Sopranos - Friends and Family#Amy Safir|Amy Safir]]. Amy works for [[Jon Favreau]], and they are filming in New York. She has been eager to meet Christopher and read his screenplay; as she says, mob-themed stories are a hit. She is also struck by Christopher as a man. At home, Adriana tells Chris she has kept a copy of the screenplay he threw away, and persuades him to pass it to Jon and Amy. Both Chris and Adriana have been invited to the film set, but he goes alone. He is absorbed by what he sees, and makes a suggestion Jon gratefully adopts.\n\nJon wants to learn from Chris about mob customs and speech. When Chris comes as arranged to his hotel room he is not available, so he calls on Amy instead. They talk, she begins to give him advice about writing a screenplay, and they have sex. Another day, he manages to catch her in the hotel lobby and they go to her room again for sex, but afterwards she is overcome by guilt. In her room Chris finds a screenplay by Jon and sees that he has stolen a mob anecdote that Chris told him in confidence. Furious, Chris searches for him, but he has returned to California. In the following days, Amy does not reply to his messages. He finally tracks her down. She tells him, \"It was wrong, with us,\" and that, for the time being, [[Hollywood]] has lost interest in mob films. She turns her back on him. \n\n[[Anthony Soprano, Jr.|A.J.]] takes [[Carmela Soprano|his mother]]'s car without permission and damages it. When his parents rebuke him he baffles them by stating that life is absurd, and he does not wish to be  [[confirmation|confirmed]] because there is no God. [[Tony Soprano|Tony]] consults [[Big Pussy Bonpensiero|Pussy]], who is A.J.'s [[Godparent|godfather]] and confirmation sponsor; Pussy says that at that age \"they get broody.\" Tony consults [[Jennifer Melfi|Dr. Melfi]], who explains that A.J. has discovered [[existentialist|existentialism]]. A.J. consults [[Livia Soprano|his grandmother]] who tells him not to expect happiness; everyone dies alone; \"It's all a big nothing.\"\n\nPussy is forced by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] to wear a [[Covert listening device|wire]] at A.J.'s confirmation and the ensuing reception at the Soprano home. During the reception, Tony discovers A.J. and two friends smoking [[marijuana]] in the garage. Pussy goes up to A.J.'s room, where he is sulking, and gently tells him that his father is a good man; A.J. is young and should enjoy life. He hugs him and sends him back down to the party, but Pussy himself goes into the toilet and sobs.    \n\nAdriana has inadvertently told Tony about the screenplay-writing. Chris misses the confirmation ceremony and arrives late for the reception. Tony then tells him he has a choice: either to follow his other interests, or to completely commit himself to him. Chris goes out and thinks it over, then goes back to Tony.<ref name=\"HBOepisode\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.hbo.com/the-sopranos/episodes#/the-sopranos/episodes/2/20-d-girl/synopsis.html\n|title=HBO: The Sopranos: S 2 EP 20 D-Girl: Synopsis\n|publisher=[[HBO]]\n|accessdate=2014-03-03}}</ref><ref name=\"The Sopranos: Episode Guide\">{{cite book\n|title=The Sopranos: The Complete Book\n|last1=O'Connor\n|first1=Mimi\n|editor1-last=Martin\n|editor1-first=Brett\n|date=2007-10-30\n|publisher=[[Time Inc.|Time]]\n|location=[[New York City|New York]]\n|isbn=978-1-933821-18-4\n|chapter=''The Sopranos'': Episode Guide\n|page=225}}</ref>\n\n==Title reference==\nThe episode's title is a shortened title for \"[[development girl]]\", used mostly in the film and television industry.\n\n==Cultural references==\n* Christopher refers to the comedy film ''[[The Gang That Couldn't Shoot Straight (film)]]'' (1971) when Favreau talks about his passion to make and star in another film about \"Crazy [[Joe Gallo]].\"\n* Amy reminds Christopher that ''[[Mickey Blue Eyes]]'' (which starred [[Vincent Pastore]]) is an example of another mob movie that failed to live up to its advance billing.\n* Adriana tells Amy and John that she enjoyed Favreau's film ''[[Swingers (1996 film)|Swingers]]'' (1996), with [[Vince Vaughn]].\n* When Carmela and Tony express concern about AJ's existentialist pronouncements, Meadow quotes [[Germaine de Sta\u00ebl|Mme de Sta\u00ebl]]:  \"One must choose in life between boredom and suffering.\u201d\n* Meadow says that A.J. has been assigned [[The_Stranger_(Camus_novel)|The Stranger]], a novel by Albert Camus. \n* When Christopher relates the story of the trans woman whose lover threw acid in her face after becoming intimate and learning that she was actually transsexual, Amy recalls the film, ''[[The Crying Game]]'' (1992).\n* Amy relates [[Maslow's hierarchy of needs]] to Christopher before becoming intimate with him.\n* When Amy tells Christopher they were wrong to have begun a relationship and Christopher responds that he really liked her, Amy observes that the mood has become rather \"[[William Inge]]\".\n\n== Music ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=September 2017}}\n* The song played over the end credits is \"Vedi, Maria\", by [[Emma Shapplin]].\n* When Chris, John, and Amy sit down at the pizza shop, the song played is \"[[Swingtown (song)|Swingtown]]\" by the [[Steve Miller Band]]. It is then followed by \"[[Rhiannon (song)|Rhiannon]]\" by [[Fleetwood Mac]].\n* Other music included in this episode includes \"Tasty Pudding\" by [[Chet Baker]], \"Shaolin Satellite\" by [[Thievery Corporation]], \"Voulez-Vous?\" by [[Arling & Cameron]], and \"Caught My Mind\" by [[Pushmonkey]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.hbo.com/the-sopranos/episodes/index.html#/the-sopranos/episodes/2/20-d-girl/index.html \"D-Girl\"] at [[HBO]]\n*{{imdb episode|0705238|D-Girl}}\n*{{tv.com episode|the-sopranos/d-girl-26467|D-Girl}}\n\n{{The Sopranos}}\n\n[[Category:The Sopranos (season 2) episodes]]\n[[Category:2000 American television episodes]]\n\n[[fr:La Garce (Les Soprano)]]\n", "name_user": "Fullmetal2887", "label": "safe", "comment": "image caption", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D-Girl_(The_Sopranos)"}
{"title_page": "White-plumed honeyeater", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = White-plumed honeyeater\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"IUCN\">{{cite iucn | authors = [[BirdLife International]] | title = Ptilotula penicillata | volume = 2016 | page = e.T22704097A93952831 | year = 2016 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T22704097A93952831.en }}</ref>\n| image = Ptilotula penicillata - Glen Davis.jpg\n| image_caption = At Glen Davis, New South Wales\n| image2 = Ptilotula penicillata - White-plumed Honeyeater XC492296.mp3\n| image2_caption = Recorded at Cooya Pooya, Western Australia\n| genus = Ptilotula\n| species = penicillata\n| authority = ([[John Gould|Gould]], 1837)\n| synonyms = ''Lichenostomus penicillatus''\n| range_map = WPHE distribution.png\n| range_map_caption = Distribution\n}}\n\nThe '''white-plumed honeyeater''' (''Ptilotula penicillata'', formerly ''Lichenostomus penicillatus''<ref name=\"IOC\">{{cite web|title=IOC Version 3.5 (Sept 30, 2013)|url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/updates/archive-3-1-to-3-5/taxonomy-3-1-3-5/|website=IOC World Bird List|accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref>) is a small [[passerine]] bird endemic to [[Australia]].  White-plumed honeyeaters are common around water and are often seen in backyards and suburbs with vegetation cover.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.birdsinbackyards.net/species/Lichenostomus-penicillatus | title=White-plumed Honeyeater &#124; BIRDS in BACKYARDS}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\n\nFirst described by English naturalist, [[John Gould]], in 1837,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gould|first1=John|title=Exhibition of the specimens figured in the first part of Mr. Gould's work, on the 'Australian Birds,' with characters of the new species|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society|date=1837|volume=5|page=143}}</ref> the specimen he examined came from \u201cthe interior of New South Wales\u201d.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gould|first1=John|title=A synopsis of the birds of Australia and the adjacent islands|date=1837|publisher=John Gould|location=London|page=69|url=https://archive.org/details/SynopsisBirdsAu00Goul|accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref> The species name ''penicillata'' derives from the [[Latin]] word ''penicillis'' meaning 'brush tip', referring to the white plume across the side of the neck.<ref name=\"HANZAB\">{{cite book |last1=Higgins |first1=P.J. |last2=Peter |first2=J.M. |last3=Steele |first3=W.K.|title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds. Tyrant-flycatchers to Chats vol. 5 |date=2001 |publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Melbourne|pages=879\u2013895}}</ref> He placed the species in ''[[Meliphaga]]'', where it would remain for almost 150 years. In 1975, Australian naturalist, [[Richard Schodde]], split ''Meliphaga'' and placed the species in ''[[Lichenostomus]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Schodde|first1=Richard|title=Interim List of Australian Songbirds. Passerines|date=1975|publisher=Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union|location=Melbourne|pages=61\u201362}}</ref> With the introduction of molecular studies, it was apparent that the white-plumed honeyeater belonged in a clade within ''Lichenostomus''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Christidis|first1=L.|last2=Schodde|first2=R.|title=Relationships and Radiations in the Meliphagine Honeyeaters, Meliphaga, Lichenostomus and Xanthotis (Aves, Meliphagidae) \u2013 Protein Evidence and Its Integration With Morphology and Ecogeography |journal=Australian Journal of Zoology|date=1993|volume=41|issue=3|pages=293\u2013316|doi=10.1071/ZO9930293}}</ref> This had first been suggested by Mathews in 1915, who placed it with the [[Yellow-tinted honeyeater]] in a genus he named ''Ptilotula'';<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mathews|first1=Gregory|title=List of birds of Australia|date=1913|publisher=Witherby & Co.|location=London|pages=280\u2013281}}</ref> but this was rejected by the [[Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Royal Australasian Ornithologists' Union Checklist Committee|title=Official checklist of the birds of Australia : supplements 1 to 9|date=1926|publisher=H. J. Green|location=Melbourne|edition=2nd}}</ref> The ''[[Ptilotula]]'' clade was finally promoted to [[genus]] after new molecular evidence was published in 2011.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nyari|first1=A.S.|last2=Joseph|first2=L.|title=Systematic dismantlement of ''Lichenostomus'' improves the basis for understanding relationships within the honeyeaters (Meliphagidae) and the historical development of Australo-Papuan bird communities |journal=Emu|date=2011|volume=111|issue=3|pages=202\u2013211 |doi=10.1071/MU10047 |url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/mu/MU10047 |accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"IOC\" />\n\nThe species is probably of [[Miocene]] origin, with a fossil fragment found in [[Australian Fossil Mammal Sites (Riversleigh)|Riversleigh]], Queensland, appearing very similar to the white-plumed honeyeater leg-bone.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Boles|first1=Walter E.|title=Fossil honeyeaters (Meliphagidae) from the Late Tertiary of Riversleigh, north-western Queensland |journal=Emu|date=2003|volume=105|issue=1|pages=21\u201326 |doi=10.1071/MU03024 |url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/mu/MU03024 |accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n\n[[File:WPHE juv 02.jpg|left|upright|thumb|alt=WPHE juv 02|A juvenile white-plumed honeyeater (''P. p. penicillatus'') at Toorale Station, NSW]] \nThe [[plumage]] does not differ between the sexes.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> The distinguishing characteristic is a conspicuous white plume across the neck from the throat to the edge of the nape. The top of head and neck are olive, with a yellow eye-ring surrounding a black-brown to olive-brown eye. Cheeks and ear coverts are yellow-olive, with the rear coverts tipped black, creating a short black stripe along the anterior edge of the neck plume. The chin and throat are dull yellowish-olive.\n\nThe upperparts are uniform grey-olive and the uppertail coverts have a yellowish tinge.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> Upperwing coverts are mostly brown with olive to yellow-olive tips or edges, creating a somewhat scalloped appearance. Remiges are dark brown with yellowish edges to secondaries, forming a yellow-olive panel when the wing is folded. Uppertail is olive-brown with yellow-olive outer edges. Underbody is mainly light brown-grey, with pale yellow streaks in the centre of the breast, pale yellow on the upper belly, flanks and undertail coverts, and cream on the lower belly. Underwing coverts are off-white with brown-grey remiges. Undertail is brownish grey.\n\nThe feet and legs are pinkish to purplish grey.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> During breeding season, the bill and gape are black; however, outside of breeding the bill obtains an orange-yellow or orange-brown base (only on the lower mandible in some individuals) with a yellow gape.\n\nFour [[subspecies]] are recognised: ''penicillatus'', ''leilavalensis'', ''carteri'' and ''calconi''.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> ''P. p. leilavalensis'' is paler and yellower, ''carteri'' is strongly tinged yellow, and ''calconi'' yellower. These subspecies intergrade where ranges overlap.\nIn all four races, males are slightly larger than females. ''P. p. penicillatus'' is the largest, with males averaging 20.5 g and females 18.1 g. ''P. p. leilavalensis'' and ''P. p. carteri'' are similar in size, where males are around 18 g and females 16 g. ''P. p. calconi'' is the smallest, with males around 17.5 g and females around 16 g. Wing lengths are much larger in ''penicillatus'', and bill lengths differ only slightly, with the bill of  ''P. p. carteri'' being somewhat longer than the other three subspecies.\n\nJuveniles are similar to adults, but with duller colours on the top of head and neck, and brighter colours on the eye-ring and ear coverts.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> The plume is shorter and less distinct, often lacking the black border of the ear coverts. Underbody is slightly more brown. The bill is pink or yellowish with a brown tip in young individuals, changing to black with a yellow-orange or pinkish base; while the gape is yellow and noticeably puffy looking. In newly fledged birds, the feet and legs are a paler pinkish-brown and appear swollen compared to the adult.\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n\nThe species is widely distributed throughout south-eastern Australia (excluding Tasmania), up towards central Australia with patches occurring in central and western Queensland, Northern Territory and Western Australia.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> They are absent from desert areas but can persist in arid regions where trees and especially standing water are present.\n\nNominate race, ''P. p. penicillatus'', occurs throughout south-eastern Australia to the Spencer Gulf in South Australia, and throughout the [[Murray-Darling basin]].<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> ''P. p. leilavalensis'' is found from [[Lake Eyre]] south to the [[Flinders Ranges]] in South Australia, east to the [[Barrier Ranges]] in western New South Wales, west to the edges of the [[Gibson desert|Gibson]] and [[Great Sandy Desert|Great Sandy]] Deserts, and north to central-western Queensland. ''P. p. carteri'' occurs in the Pilbara region of WA from [[Geraldton]] to the Fortescue Ranges, and east to the Western Deserts; while ''P. p. calconi'' is known only from the southern [[Kimberley (Western Australia)|Kimberley]] region.\n\nThe species has undergone range expansion in the last century.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /><ref name=\"Hindwood\">{{cite journal |last1=Hindwood |first1=K.A. |title=Breeding of the White-plumed honeyeater near Sydney|journal=Emu|date=1950|volume=49|issue=3|pages=211\u2013213 |doi=10.1071/MU949211}}</ref>  It was formerly linked closely to the distribution of [[river red gum]] (''Eucalyptus camaldulensis'') and a few other riverine species;<ref name=\"Gannon\">{{cite journal|last1=Gannon|first1=G.R.|title=The influence of habitat on the distribution of Australian birds.|journal=Emu|date=1965|volume=65|issue=4|pages=241\u2013253|doi=10.1071/MU965241}}</ref> but it has since expanded into coastal areas to become resident in Sydney and Newcastle, where they were previously uncommon or only seasonal visitors.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /><ref name=\"Hindwood\" /> Banding studies indicate that the species is primarily sedentary, with 99.8% of recaptures occurring less than 10&nbsp;km from the banding site. Small local movements occur, perhaps in response to environmental conditions.\n\nAn oligotypic species,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=MacNally|first1=R.|title=A protocol for classifying regional dynamics, exemplified by using woodland birds in southeastern Australia|journal=Australian Journal of Ecology|date=1995|volume=20|issue=3|pages=442\u2013454 |doi=10.1111/j.1442-9993.1995.tb00560.x}}</ref> it is mainly found in open sclerophyll woodland, often near water sources, such as wetlands, swamps, creeks, and dams.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> It is found extensively in river red gum woodlands,<ref name=\"Gannon\" /> but also riparian woodlands dominated by [[Eucalyptus]], [[Melaleuca]] or [[Casuarina]] species. It may also be found in nearby river flats or open forest and woodland.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /><ref name=\"Chan\">{{cite journal|last1=Chan|first1=K.|title=Habitat selection in the White-plumed Honeyeater and the Fuscous Honeyeater at an area of sympatry|journal=Australian Journal of Ecology |date=1990 |volume=15 |issue=2 |pages=207\u2013217 |doi=10.1111/j.1442-9993.1990.tb01529.x}}</ref><ref name=\"Ford and Paton 77\">{{cite journal |last1=Ford |first1=H.A. |last2=Paton |first2=D.C.|title=The comparative ecology of ten species of honeyeaters in South Australia|journal=Australian Journal of Ecology |date=1977|volume=4|issue=2|pages=399\u2013407|doi=10.1111/j.1442-9993.1977.tb01155.x}}</ref><ref name=\"Ford and Paton 76\">{{cite journal |last1=Ford|first1=H.A.|last2=Paton|first2=D.C.|title=Resource partitioning and competition in honeyeaters of the genus Meliphaga |journal=Australian Journal of Ecology|date=1976|volume=1|issue=4|pages=281\u2013287|doi=10.1111/j.1442-9993.1976.tb01118.x}}</ref>\n\n==Diet==\nThe white-plumed honeyeater's diet consists mainly of nectar, insects and their products (e.g., honeydew and lerp), manna, fruit, and very occasionally seeds.<ref name=\"Ford and Paton 76\" /><ref name=\"Berney\">{{cite journal|last1=Berney|first1=Fred L.|title=Food of Australian Birds|journal=Emu|date=1907|volume=7|issue=2|pages=79\u201381 |doi=10.1071/MU907079|url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/mu/pdf/MU907079|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Chan\" /><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Paton|first1=D.C.|last2=Ford|first2=H.A.|title=Pollination by birds of native plants in South Australia |journal=Emu |date=1977 |volume=77|issue=2|pages=73\u201385|doi=10.1071/MU9770073|url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/mu/MU9770073}}</ref><ref name=\"Paton 1980\">{{cite journal|last1=Paton|first1=D.C.|title=The importance of manna, honeydew and lerp in the diets of honeyeaters. |journal=Emu |date=1980 |volume=80|issue=4|pages=213\u2013226 |doi=10.1080/01584197.1980.11799277|url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/mu/pdf/MU9800213|accessdate=15 December 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lepschi|first1=B.J.|title=Food of Some Birds in Eastern New South Wales: Additions to Barker & Vestjens |journal=Emu |date=1993|volume=93|issue=3|pages=195\u2013199 |doi=10.1071/MU9930195|url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/mu/pdf/MU9930195|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lepschi|first1=B.J.|title=Food of Some Birds in Southern Australia: Additions to Barker & Vestjens, Part 2 |journal=Emu |date=1997 |volume=97|issue=1|pages=84\u201387|doi=10.1071/MU97009}}</ref> They may also peck at berries to feed on juice.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cohn|first1=M.|title=Birds and ''Crataegus'' berries|journal=Emu|date=1942|volume=42|issue=2|page=122|doi=10.1071/MU942122a}}</ref>\n\nWhere sufficient standing water occurs, ''P. penicillata'' can be observed drinking at least twice per day.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> In xeric habitats, additional moisture is obtained from food.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Prinzinger |first1=Roland |last2=Schleucher |first2=Elke |title=Fruits of Tall Saltbush Rhagodia eremaea as an Important Source of Energy and Water for Arid Zone Honeyeaters |journal=Emu |date=1998|volume=98|issue=3|pages=236\u2013240|doi=10.1071/MU98033|url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/mu/MU98033|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref> A study in the [[Pilbara]] region of Western Australia found that white-plumed honeyeaters must eat around 100 berries to obtain 1mL of water. Needing 5-10mL per day, white-plumed honeyeaters were able to feed on 500\u20131000 berries in a five-hour period in order to obtain both caloric requirements and sufficient water intake.\n\n===Foraging behaviour===\nWhite-plumed honeyeaters mainly feed by gleaning leaf surfaces.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> The tongue contains brush-like filaments, consisting of about 60 bristles, which are capable of mopping up nectar.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Paton |first1=D.C. |last2=COLLINS |first2=B.G. |title=Bills and tongues of nectar-feeding birds: A review of morphology, function and performance, with intercontinental comparisons |journal=Austral Ecology|date=1989|volume=14|issue=4|pages=473\u2013506|doi=10.1111/j.1442-9993.1989.tb01457.x}}</ref> Arthropod prey is usually taken by gleaning, but some prey is taken on the wing.<ref name=\"Ford and Paton 1976\">{{cite journal |last1=Ford |first1=H.A. |last2=Paton |first2=D.C.|title=The value of insects and nectar to honeyeaters|journal=Emu|date=1976|volume=76|issue=2|pages=83\u201384 |doi=10.1071/MU9760083 |url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/MU/pdf/MU9760083|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn urban areas, they are typically canopy foragers<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Palmer|first1=Grant C.|last2=Fitzsimons|first2=James A. |last3=Antos |first3=Mark J.|last4=White|first4=John G.|title=Determinants of native avian richness in suburban remnant vegetation: Implications for conservation planning|journal=Biological Conservation|date=2008|volume=141|issue=9|pages=2329\u20132341 |doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2008.06.025}}</ref> but foraging heights can vary, depending on the influence of other resident species. For example, in the presence of aggressive competitors, such as [[fuscous honeyeater]]s, white-plumed honeyeaters avoid conflict by modifying their foraging behaviour.<ref name=\"Chan\" /> In one location, where ranges of the two species overlapped, white-plumed honeyeaters fed at lower heights in the overlap zone than they did in the riparian zone, where fuscous honeyeaters were absent.\n\nInformation on diet comes from scats, stomach contents, and foraging observations. Stomach contents are heavily biased toward strong tissues from plants and arthropods.<ref name=\"Berney\" /> In 1980, it was found that manna, honeydew, and lerp were extremely important food resources.<ref name=\"Paton 1980\" /> Other research indicated that insects were only a small part of the diet,<ref name=\"Ford and Paton 76\" /> when they were previously thought to be major components.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lea |first1=A.M. |last2=Grey |first2=J.T. |title=The food of Australian birds (An Analysis of the Stomach Contents) \u2013 Part IV |journal=Emu |date=1935 |volume=35 |issue=3 |pages=251\u2013280|doi=10.1071/MU935251}}</ref> Insects are sometimes taken on the wing, but probably only provide a protein and mineral source, as a surplus of energy is available in nectar, lerp, and manna. The lower proportion of insects in the diet is a consequence of the fact that more energy is spent hawking prey than can be redeemed from the prey.<ref name=\"Ford and Paton 1976\" />\n\n==Social behaviour==\n\nThis is a gregarious species, often found in groups of 12 or more individuals during the nonbreeding season. These larger groups then dissipate during breeding.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> ''P. penicillata'' is considered colonial, with observations of colonies throughout their range. There is some suggestion of [[cooperative breeding]], but if occurring it is uncommon. Communal breeding is likely, with conspecifics grouping to attack predators near nests. However, individual territories within communities are maintained, with territorial song frequency increasing during the breeding season.\n\nExperiments with captive populations indicate that hierarchies form, based on plumage colour, gape flange characters, and voice,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ives|first1=N.L.|title=Devices for reducing aggression in the White-plumed Honeyeater and the Willie Wagtail |journal=Emu |date=1975 |volume=75|issue=1|pages=40\u201342 |doi=10.1071/MU9750040|url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/MU/pdf/MU9750040|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref> but no data from wild populations exists.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> Observations of aggressive interactions between conspecifics and other species, such as the [[yellow-faced honeyeater]] (''Caligavis chrysops''), [[willie wagtail]] (''Rhipidura leucophrys''), [[red wattlebird]] (''Anthochaera carunculata''), and smaller species, such as [[pardalote]]s (''Pardalotus'' spp.), [[mistletoebird]] (''Dicaeum hirundinaceum''), and other small honeyeaters have been made. There are some observations of attacks on [[fuscous honeyeater]]s, but the two species tend to avoid each other, where they occur sympatrically.<ref name=\"Chan\" /> In some regions, smaller birds are absent, due to the aggressive nature of white-plumed honeyeaters and other species of similar size, resulting in the exclusion of these poorer competitors.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pavey|first1=C.R.|last2=Nano|first2=C.E.M|title=Bird assemblages of arid Australia: Vegetation patterns have a greater effect than disturbance and resource pulses|journal=Journal of Arid Environments|date=2009|volume=73|issue=6\u20137 |pages=634\u2013642 |doi=10.1016/j.jaridenv.2009.01.010}}</ref>\n\nForaging groups may use a ''chip-chip'' contact call, or a song which is repeated by nearby individuals.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> Corroborees of up to 12 or more individuals, sitting together on a branch, have been observed, which engage in extensive calling, followed by rapid dispersal.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n==Reproduction==\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2017}}\n[[File:Lichenostomus penicillatus nest from side.JPG|thumb|left|alt=The cup nest|The cup nest]][[File:Lichenostomus penicillatus nest with 2 eggs.JPG|thumb|left|alt=Nest with two eggs|Nest with two eggs]]Females are relatively more ready to breed from late winter through to summer;<ref name=\"Buttemer\">{{cite journal |last1=Buttemer |first1=W.A. |last2=Addison |first2=B.A. |last3=Astheimer |first3=L.B. |title=Lack of seasonal and moult-related stress modulation in an opportunistically breeding bird: The white-plumed honeyeater (''Lichenostomus penicillatus'') |journal=Hormones and Behavior|date=2015|volume=76|pages=34\u201340 |doi=10.1016/j.yhbeh.2015.02.002|pmid=25701624}}</ref> however, males maintain enlarged testes throughout the year.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Astheimer |first1=Lee B.|last2=Buttemer|first2=William A.|title=Changes in latitude, changes in attitude: a perspective on ecophysiological studies of Australian birds|journal=Emu|date=2002|volume=102|issue=1|pages=19\u201327 |doi=10.1071/MU01031 |url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/mu/MU01031|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref> Breeding occurs throughout their range with records in all months, and clutches typically produced 2\u20133 times per year.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> Breeding events usually coincide with outbreaks of herbivorous insects.<ref name=\"Buttemer\" />\n\nNests are small and cup-shaped, 5\u20136&nbsp;cm diameter and similar depth.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> These are skillfully woven from grasses, bound with spider's silk, animal hair or wool; and can include feathers and plant material. The female appears to be responsible for construction, but both sexes maintain and make repairs. Nests are usually located among the foliage in crowns of trees or shrubs, and only rarely seen in mistletoe. Sometimes nests are constructed in forks or on branches, and rarely in dead foliage. There is some evidence of site fidelity, and nest trees may be shared with active nests maintained by several other species, including [[Willie wagtail|wagtails]], [[magpie-lark]], [[dusky woodswallow|woodswallows]], and other honeyeater species.\n\nMales undertake a song flight display, with a slight climbing and undulating flight above treetops while singing.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> At the song's completion, the male dives quickly into a nearby tree. This is performed throughout the day during breeding season, but less commonly in the early morning. Playback of this song does not induce territorial responses, suggesting the display is sexual in function. Other songs heard commonly after the breeding period begins may also have courtship functions.\n\nThe clutch is usually 2\u20133 eggs, varying from 1\u20134 overall.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> The second egg is typically laid within 24 hours of the first. Eggs are approximately 20 x 15&nbsp;cm, weighing 2.45g; oval, smooth, finely grained, and may be slightly glossy. Colour varies from white to yellowish, light red or pink. Markings may vary from uniform reddish freckles to purplish or dark reddish-brown spots. Marks are sometimes in greater frequency at the large end. Eggs laid late in season tend to be lighter, and those from inland populations tend to be white with fewer markings.\n\nDetails about incubation duties are unknown, although they are thought to be performed only by the female. Eggs are incubated for 10\u201314 days before hatching. Both sexes feed offspring with females brooding, leaving only when the male arrives to feed chicks. Both parents remove faecal sacs and eggshell fragments. Parents undertake distraction displays when predators approach nests, mainly in the final days before nestlings fledge. Fledging occurs 12\u201313 days after hatching and juveniles are fed for two or more weeks after leaving nest.\n\nWhite-plumed honeyeaters are parasitised by [[Pallid cuckoo|pallid]] and [[Fan-tailed cuckoo|fan-tailed]] cuckoos, as well as [[Horsfield's bronze-cuckoo|Horsfield's]]  and [[Shining bronze-cuckoo|shining]] bronze-cuckoos.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" />\n\n==Conservation status==\n\nThe white-plumed honeyeater is considered by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) to be of [[least concern]] for conservation.<ref name=\"IUCN\" />\n\n===Threats===\n\nExotic vertebrate predators, such as cats and dogs, are a direct threat to white-plumed honeyeater populations.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" />\nLoss of trees from watercourses will impact a population; however, they are able to adapt to suburban environments, especially where native gardens are present.\n\n===Climate effects===\n\nThe white-plumed honeyeater body-size has been observed to change over recent decades, with individuals becoming smaller in extended drought, but showing an overall trend towards larger body-size since the 1960s.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gardner|first1=Janet L. |last2=Amano |first2=Tatsuya |last3=Mackey|first3=Brendan G.|last4=Sutherland|first4=William J. |last5=Clayton |first5=Mark |last6=Peters |first6=Anne |title=Dynamic size responses to climate change: prevailing effects of rising temperature drive long-term body size increases in a semi-arid passerine|journal=Global Change Biology|date=2014|volume=2|issue=7|pages=2062\u20132075|doi=10.1111/gcb.12507}}</ref> This is correlated with increasing temperatures in the regions surveyed, with body size increasing by 0.064% per year.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gardner|first1=Janet L.|last2=Amano|first2=Tatsuya|last3=Backwell|first3=Patrica R.Y. |last4=Ikin |first4=Karen |last5=Sutherland |first5=William J.|last6=Peters|first6=Anne|title=Temporal patterns of avian body size reflect linear size responses to broadscale environmental change over the last 50 years|journal=Journal of Avian Biology|date=2014|volume=45|issue=6|pages=529\u2013535 |doi=10.1111/jav.00431}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Commons|Lichenostomus penicillatus}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.xeno-canto.org/species/Ptilotula-penicillata White plumed honeyeater sound recordings at Xeno Canto] \n*[http://bie.ala.org.au/species/urn:lsid:biodiversity.org.au:afd.taxon:a98f7d77-5d5b-48a0-a38f-a4ceaadb5d89 Distribution information at Atlas of Living Australia]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q27075261}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:honeyeater, white-plumed}}\n[[Category:Ptilotula|white-plumed honeyeater]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1837|white-plumed honeyeater]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{speciesbox\n| name = White-plumed honeyeater\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"IUCN\">{{cite iucn | authors = [[BirdLife International]] | title = Ptilotula penicillata | volume = 2016 | page = e.T22704097A93952831 | year = 2016 | doi = 10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-3.RLTS.T22704097A93952831.en }}</ref>\n| image = Ptilotula penicillata - Glen Davis.jpg\n| image_caption = At Glen Davis, New South Wales\n| image2 = Ptilotula penicillata - White-plumed Honeyeater XC492296.mp3\n| image2_caption = Recorded at Cooya Pooya, Western Australia\n| genus = Ptilotula\n| species = penicillata\n| authority = ([[John Gould|Gould]], 1837)\n| synonyms = ''Lichenostomus penicillatus''\n| range_map = WPHE distribution.png\n| range_map_caption = Distribution\n}}\n\nThe '''white-plumed honeyeater''' (''Ptilotula penicillata'', formerly ''Lichenostomus penicillatus''<ref name=\"IOC\">{{cite web|title=IOC Version 3.5 (Sept 30, 2013)|url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/updates/archive-3-1-to-3-5/taxonomy-3-1-3-5/|website=IOC World Bird List|accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref>) is a small [[passerine]] bird endemic to [[Australia]].  White-plumed honeyeaters are common around water and are often seen in backyards and suburbs with vegetation cover.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.birdsinbackyards.net/species/Lichenostomus-penicillatus | title=White-plumed Honeyeater &#124; BIRDS in BACKYARDS}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy==\n\nFirst described by English naturalist, [[John Gould]], in 1837,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gould|first1=John|title=Exhibition of the specimens figured in the first part of Mr. Gould's work, on the 'Australian Birds,' with characters of the new species|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society|date=1837|volume=5|page=143}}</ref> the specimen he examined came from \u201cthe interior of New South Wales\u201d.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Gould|first1=John|title=A synopsis of the birds of Australia and the adjacent islands|date=1837|publisher=John Gould|location=London|page=69|url=https://archive.org/details/SynopsisBirdsAu00Goul|accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref> The species name ''penicillata'' derives from the [[Latin]] word ''penicillis'' meaning 'brush tip', referring to the white plume across the side of the neck.<ref name=\"HANZAB\">{{cite book |last1=Higgins |first1=P.J. |last2=Peter |first2=J.M. |last3=Steele |first3=W.K.|title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand and Antarctic Birds. Tyrant-flycatchers to Chats vol. 5 |date=2001 |publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Melbourne|pages=879\u2013895}}</ref> He placed the species in ''[[Meliphaga]]'', where it would remain for almost 150 years. In 1975, Australian naturalist, [[Richard Schodde]], split ''Meliphaga'' and placed the species in ''[[Lichenostomus]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Schodde|first1=Richard|title=Interim List of Australian Songbirds. Passerines|date=1975|publisher=Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union|location=Melbourne|pages=61\u201362}}</ref> With the introduction of molecular studies, it was apparent that the white-plumed honeyeater belonged in a clade within ''Lichenostomus''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Christidis|first1=L.|last2=Schodde|first2=R.|title=Relationships and Radiations in the Meliphagine Honeyeaters, Meliphaga, Lichenostomus and Xanthotis (Aves, Meliphagidae) \u2013 Protein Evidence and Its Integration With Morphology and Ecogeography |journal=Australian Journal of Zoology|date=1993|volume=41|issue=3|pages=293\u2013316|doi=10.1071/ZO9930293}}</ref> This had first been suggested by Mathews in 1915, who placed it with the [[Yellow-tinted honeyeater]] in a genus he named ''Ptilotula'';<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mathews|first1=Gregory|title=List of birds of Australia|date=1913|publisher=Witherby & Co.|location=London|pages=280\u2013281}}</ref> but this was rejected by the [[Royal Australasian Ornithologists Union]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Royal Australasian Ornithologists' Union Checklist Committee|title=Official checklist of the birds of Australia : supplements 1 to 9|date=1926|publisher=H. J. Green|location=Melbourne|edition=2nd}}</ref> The ''[[Ptilotula]]'' clade was finally promoted to [[genus]] after new molecular evidence was published in 2011.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nyari|first1=A.S.|last2=Joseph|first2=L.|title=Systematic dismantlement of ''Lichenostomus'' improves the basis for understanding relationships within the honeyeaters (Meliphagidae) and the historical development of Australo-Papuan bird communities |journal=Emu|date=2011|volume=111|issue=3|pages=202\u2013211 |doi=10.1071/MU10047 |url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/mu/MU10047 |accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"IOC\" />\n\nThe species is probably of [[Miocene]] origin, with a fossil fragment found in [[Australian Fossil Mammal Sites (Riversleigh)|Riversleigh]], Queensland, appearing very similar to the white-plumed honeyeater leg-bone.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Boles|first1=Walter E.|title=Fossil honeyeaters (Meliphagidae) from the Late Tertiary of Riversleigh, north-western Queensland |journal=Emu|date=2003|volume=105|issue=1|pages=21\u201326 |doi=10.1071/MU03024 |url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/mu/MU03024 |accessdate=14 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n\n[[File:WPHE juv 02.jpg|left|upright|thumb|alt=WPHE juv 02|A juvenile white-plumed honeyeater (''P. p. penicillatus'') at Toorale Station, NSW]] \nThe [[plumage]] does not differ between the sexes.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> The distinguishing characteristic is a conspicuous white plume across the neck from the throat to the edge of the nape. The top of head and neck are olive, with a yellow eye-ring surrounding a black-brown to olive-brown eye. Cheeks and ear coverts are yellow-olive, with the rear coverts tipped black, creating a short black stripe along the anterior edge of the neck plume. The chin and throat are dull yellowish-olive.\n\nThe upperparts are uniform grey-olive and the uppertail coverts have a yellowish tinge.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> Upperwing coverts are mostly brown with olive to yellow-olive tips or edges, creating a somewhat scalloped appearance. Remiges are dark brown with yellowish edges to secondaries, forming a yellow-olive panel when the wing is folded. Uppertail is olive-brown with yellow-olive outer edges. Underbody is mainly light brown-grey, with pale yellow streaks in the centre of the breast, pale yellow on the upper belly, flanks and undertail coverts, and cream on the lower belly. Underwing coverts are off-white with brown-grey remiges. Undertail is brownish grey.\n\nThe feet and legs are pinkish to purplish grey.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> During breeding season, the bill and gape are black; however, outside of breeding the bill obtains an orange-yellow or orange-brown base (only on the lower mandible in some individuals) with a yellow gape.\n\nFour [[subspecies]] are recognised: ''penicillatus'', ''leilavalensis'', ''carteri'' and ''calconi''.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> ''P. p. leilavalensis'' is paler and yellower, ''carteri'' is strongly tinged yellow, and ''calconi'' yellower. These subspecies intergrade where ranges overlap.\nIn all four races, males are slightly larger than females. ''P. p. penicillatus'' is the largest, with males averaging 20.5 g and females 18.1 g. ''P. p. leilavalensis'' and ''P. p. carteri'' are similar in size, where males are around 18 g and females 16 g. ''P. p. calconi'' is the smallest, with males around 17.5 g and females around 16 g. Wing lengths are much larger in ''penicillatus'', and bill lengths differ only slightly, with the bill of  ''P. p. carteri'' being somewhat longer than the other three subspecies.\n\nJuveniles are similar to adults, but with duller colours on the top of head and neck, and brighter colours on the eye-ring and ear coverts.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> The plume is shorter and less distinct, often lacking the black border of the ear coverts. Underbody is slightly more brown. The bill is pink or yellowish with a brown tip in young individuals, changing to black with a yellow-orange or pinkish base; while the gape is yellow and noticeably puffy looking. In newly fledged birds, the feet and legs are a paler pinkish-brown and appear swollen compared to the adult.\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\n\nThe species is widely distributed throughout south-eastern Australia (excluding Tasmania), up towards central Australia with patches occurring in central and western Queensland, Northern Territory and Western Australia.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> They are absent from desert areas but can persist in arid regions where trees and especially standing water are present.\n\nNominate race, ''P. p. penicillatus'', occurs throughout south-eastern Australia to the Spencer Gulf in South Australia, and throughout the [[Murray-Darling basin]].<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> ''P. p. leilavalensis'' is found from [[Lake Eyre]] south to the [[Flinders Ranges]] in South Australia, east to the [[Barrier Ranges]] in western New South Wales, west to the edges of the [[Gibson desert|Gibson]] and [[Great Sandy Desert|Great Sandy]] Deserts, and north to central-western Queensland. ''P. p. carteri'' occurs in the Pilbara region of WA from [[Geraldton]] to the Fortescue Ranges, and east to the Western Deserts; while ''P. p. calconi'' is known only from the southern [[Kimberley (Western Australia)|Kimberley]] region.\n\nThe species has undergone range expansion in the last century.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /><ref name=\"Hindwood\">{{cite journal |last1=Hindwood |first1=K.A. |title=Breeding of the White-plumed honeyeater near Sydney|journal=Emu|date=1950|volume=49|issue=3|pages=211\u2013213 |doi=10.1071/MU949211}}</ref>  It was formerly linked closely to the distribution of [[river red gum]] (''Eucalyptus camaldulensis'') and a few other riverine species;<ref name=\"Gannon\">{{cite journal|last1=Gannon|first1=G.R.|title=The influence of habitat on the distribution of Australian birds.|journal=Emu|date=1965|volume=65|issue=4|pages=241\u2013253|doi=10.1071/MU965241}}</ref> but it has since expanded into coastal areas to become resident in Sydney and Newcastle, where they were previously uncommon or only seasonal visitors.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /><ref name=\"Hindwood\" /> Banding studies indicate that the species is primarily sedentary, with 99.8% of recaptures occurring less than 10&nbsp;km from the banding site. Small local movements occur, perhaps in response to environmental conditions.\n\nAn oligotypic species,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=MacNally|first1=R.|title=A protocol for classifying regional dynamics, exemplified by using woodland birds in southeastern Australia|journal=Australian Journal of Ecology|date=1995|volume=20|issue=3|pages=442\u2013454 |doi=10.1111/j.1442-9993.1995.tb00560.x}}</ref> it is mainly found in open sclerophyll woodland, often near water sources, such as wetlands, swamps, creeks, and dams.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> It is found extensively in river red gum woodlands,<ref name=\"Gannon\" /> but also riparian woodlands dominated by [[Eucalyptus]], [[Melaleuca]] or [[Casuarina]] species. It may also be found in nearby river flats or open forest and woodland.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /><ref name=\"Chan\">{{cite journal|last1=Chan|first1=K.|title=Habitat selection in the White-plumed Honeyeater and the Fuscous Honeyeater at an area of sympatry|journal=Australian Journal of Ecology |date=1990 |volume=15 |issue=2 |pages=207\u2013217 |doi=10.1111/j.1442-9993.1990.tb01529.x}}</ref><ref name=\"Ford and Paton 77\">{{cite journal |last1=Ford |first1=H.A. |last2=Paton |first2=D.C.|title=The comparative ecology of ten species of honeyeaters in South Australia|journal=Australian Journal of Ecology |date=1977|volume=4|issue=2|pages=399\u2013407|doi=10.1111/j.1442-9993.1977.tb01155.x}}</ref><ref name=\"Ford and Paton 76\">{{cite journal |last1=Ford|first1=H.A.|last2=Paton|first2=D.C.|title=Resource partitioning and competition in honeyeaters of the genus Meliphaga |journal=Australian Journal of Ecology|date=1976|volume=1|issue=4|pages=281\u2013287|doi=10.1111/j.1442-9993.1976.tb01118.x}}</ref>\n\n==Diet==\nThe white-plumed honeyeater's diet consists mainly of nectar, insects and their products (e.g., honeydew and lerp), manna, fruit, and very occasionally seeds.<ref name=\"Ford and Paton 76\" /><ref name=\"Berney\">{{cite journal|last1=Berney|first1=Fred L.|title=Food of Australian Birds|journal=Emu|date=1907|volume=7|issue=2|pages=79\u201381 |doi=10.1071/MU907079|url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/mu/pdf/MU907079|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Chan\" /><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Paton|first1=D.C.|last2=Ford|first2=H.A.|title=Pollination by birds of native plants in South Australia |journal=Emu |date=1977 |volume=77|issue=2|pages=73\u201385|doi=10.1071/MU9770073|url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/mu/MU9770073}}</ref><ref name=\"Paton 1980\">{{cite journal|last1=Paton|first1=D.C.|title=The importance of manna, honeydew and lerp in the diets of honeyeaters. |journal=Emu |date=1980 |volume=80|issue=4|pages=213\u2013226 |doi=10.1080/01584197.1980.11799277|url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/mu/pdf/MU9800213|accessdate=15 December 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lepschi|first1=B.J.|title=Food of Some Birds in Eastern New South Wales: Additions to Barker & Vestjens |journal=Emu |date=1993|volume=93|issue=3|pages=195\u2013199 |doi=10.1071/MU9930195|url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/mu/pdf/MU9930195|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lepschi|first1=B.J.|title=Food of Some Birds in Southern Australia: Additions to Barker & Vestjens, Part 2 |journal=Emu |date=1997 |volume=97|issue=1|pages=84\u201387|doi=10.1071/MU97009}}</ref> They may also peck at berries to feed on juice.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Cohn|first1=M.|title=Birds and ''Crataegus'' berries|journal=Emu|date=1942|volume=42|issue=2|page=122|doi=10.1071/MU942122a}}</ref>\n\nWhere sufficient standing water occurs, ''P. penicillata'' can be observed drinking at least twice per day.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> In xeric habitats, additional moisture is obtained from food.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Prinzinger |first1=Roland |last2=Schleucher |first2=Elke |title=Fruits of Tall Saltbush Rhagodia eremaea as an Important Source of Energy and Water for Arid Zone Honeyeaters |journal=Emu |date=1998|volume=98|issue=3|pages=236\u2013240|doi=10.1071/MU98033|url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/mu/MU98033|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref> A study in the [[Pilbara]] region of Western Australia found that white-plumed honeyeaters must eat around 100 berries to obtain 1mL of water. Needing 5-10mL per day, white-plumed honeyeaters were able to feed on 500\u20131000 berries in a five-hour period in order to obtain both caloric requirements and sufficient water intake.\n\n===Foraging behaviour===\nWhite-plumed honeyeaters mainly feed by gleaning leaf surfaces.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> The tongue contains brush-like filaments, consisting of about 60 bristles, which are capable of mopping up nectar.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Paton |first1=D.C. |last2=COLLINS |first2=B.G. |title=Bills and tongues of nectar-feeding birds: A review of morphology, function and performance, with intercontinental comparisons |journal=Austral Ecology|date=1989|volume=14|issue=4|pages=473\u2013506|doi=10.1111/j.1442-9993.1989.tb01457.x}}</ref> Arthropod prey is usually taken by gleaning, but some prey is taken on the wing.<ref name=\"Ford and Paton 1976\">{{cite journal |last1=Ford |first1=H.A. |last2=Paton |first2=D.C.|title=The value of insects and nectar to honeyeaters|journal=Emu|date=1976|volume=76|issue=2|pages=83\u201384 |doi=10.1071/MU9760083 |url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/MU/pdf/MU9760083|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn urban areas, they are typically canopy foragers<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Palmer|first1=Grant C.|last2=Fitzsimons|first2=James A. |last3=Antos |first3=Mark J.|last4=White|first4=John G.|title=Determinants of native avian richness in suburban remnant vegetation: Implications for conservation planning|journal=Biological Conservation|date=2008|volume=141|issue=9|pages=2329\u20132341 |doi=10.1016/j.biocon.2008.06.025}}</ref> but foraging heights can vary, depending on the influence of other resident species. For example, in the presence of aggressive competitors, such as [[fuscous honeyeater]]s, white-plumed honeyeaters avoid conflict by modifying their foraging behaviour.<ref name=\"Chan\" /> In one location, where ranges of the two species overlapped, white-plumed honeyeaters fed at lower heights in the overlap zone than they did in the riparian zone, where fuscous honeyeaters were absent.\n\nInformation on diet comes from scats, stomach contents, and foraging observations. Stomach contents are heavily biased toward strong tissues from plants and arthropods.<ref name=\"Berney\" /> In 1980, it was found that manna, honeydew, and lerp were extremely important food resources.<ref name=\"Paton 1980\" /> Other research indicated that insects were only a small part of the diet,<ref name=\"Ford and Paton 76\" /> when they were previously thought to be major components.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lea |first1=A.M. |last2=Grey |first2=J.T. |title=The food of Australian birds (An Analysis of the Stomach Contents) \u2013 Part IV |journal=Emu |date=1935 |volume=35 |issue=3 |pages=251\u2013280|doi=10.1071/MU935251}}</ref> Insects are sometimes taken on the wing, but probably only provide a protein and mineral source, as a surplus of energy is available in nectar, lerp, and manna. The lower proportion of insects in the diet is a consequence of the fact that more energy is spent hawking prey than can be redeemed from the prey.<ref name=\"Ford and Paton 1976\" />\n\n==Social behaviour==\n\nThis is a gregarious species, often found in groups of 12 or more individuals during the nonbreeding season. These larger groups then dissipate during breeding.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> ''P. penicillata'' is considered colonial, with observations of colonies throughout their range. There is some suggestion of [[cooperative breeding]], but if occurring it is uncommon. Communal breeding is likely, with conspecifics grouping to attack predators near nests. However, individual territories within communities are maintained, with territorial song frequency increasing during the breeding season.\n\nExperiments with captive populations indicate that hierarchies form, based on plumage colour, gape flange characters, and voice,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ives|first1=N.L.|title=Devices for reducing aggression in the White-plumed Honeyeater and the Willie Wagtail |journal=Emu |date=1975 |volume=75|issue=1|pages=40\u201342 |doi=10.1071/MU9750040|url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/MU/pdf/MU9750040|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref> but no data from wild populations exists.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> Observations of aggressive interactions between conspecifics and other species, such as the [[yellow-faced honeyeater]] (''Caligavis chrysops''), [[willie wagtail]] (''Rhipidura leucophrys''), [[red wattlebird]] (''Anthochaera carunculata''), and smaller species, such as [[pardalote]]s (''Pardalotus'' spp.), [[mistletoebird]] (''Dicaeum hirundinaceum''), and other small honeyeaters have been made. There are some observations of attacks on [[fuscous honeyeater]]s, but the two species tend to avoid each other, where they occur sympatrically.<ref name=\"Chan\" /> In some regions, smaller birds are absent, due to the aggressive nature of white-plumed honeyeaters and other species of similar size, resulting in the exclusion of these poorer competitors.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pavey|first1=C.R.|last2=Nano|first2=C.E.M|title=Bird assemblages of arid Australia: Vegetation patterns have a greater effect than disturbance and resource pulses|journal=Journal of Arid Environments|date=2009|volume=73|issue=6\u20137 |pages=634\u2013642 |doi=10.1016/j.jaridenv.2009.01.010}}</ref>\n\nForaging groups may use a ''chip-chip'' contact call, or a song which is repeated by nearby individuals.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> Corroborees of up to 12 or more individuals, sitting together on a branch, have been observed, which engage in extensive calling, followed by rapid dispersal.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n==Reproduction==\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2017}}\n[[File:Lichenostomus penicillatus nest from side.JPG|thumb|left|alt=The cup nest|The cup nest]][[File:Lichenostomus penicillatus nest with 2 eggs.JPG|thumb|left|alt=Nest with two eggs|Nest with two eggs]]Females are relatively more ready to breed from late winter through to summer,<ref name=\"Buttemer\">{{cite journal |last1=Buttemer |first1=W.A. |last2=Addison |first2=B.A. |last3=Astheimer |first3=L.B. |title=Lack of seasonal and moult-related stress modulation in an opportunistically breeding bird: The white-plumed honeyeater (''Lichenostomus penicillatus'') |journal=Hormones and Behavior|date=2015|volume=76|pages=34\u201340 |doi=10.1016/j.yhbeh.2015.02.002|pmid=25701624}}</ref> however males maintain enlarged testes throughout the year.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Astheimer |first1=Lee B.|last2=Buttemer|first2=William A.|title=Changes in latitude, changes in attitude: a perspective on ecophysiological studies of Australian birds|journal=Emu|date=2002|volume=102|issue=1|pages=19\u201327 |doi=10.1071/MU01031 |url=http://www.publish.csiro.au/mu/MU01031|accessdate=15 December 2016}}</ref> Breeding occurs throughout the range with records in all months, and clutches typically produced 2\u20133 times per year.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> Breeding events usually coincide with outbreaks of herbivorous insects.<ref name=\"Buttemer\" />\n\nNests are small and cup-shaped, 5\u20136&nbsp;cm diameter and similar depth.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> These are skillfully woven from grasses, bound with spider's silk, animal hair or wool; and can include feathers and plant material. The female appears to be responsible for construction but both sexes maintain and make repairs. Nests are usually located among the foliage in crowns of trees or shrubs, and only rarely seen in mistletoe. Sometimes nests are constructed in forks or on branches, and rarely in dead foliage. There is some evidence of site fidelity, and nest trees may be shared with active nests maintained by several other species including [[Willie wagtail|wagtails]], [[magpie-lark]], [[dusky woodswallow|woodswallows]] and other honeyeater species.\n\nMales undertake a song flight display, with a slight climbing and undulating flight above tree tops while singing.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> At the song's completion, the male dives quickly into a nearby tree. This is performed throughout the day during breeding season, but less commonly in the early morning. Playback of this song does not induce territorial responses, suggesting the display is sexual in function. Other songs heard commonly after the breeding period begins may also have courtship functions.\n\nThe clutch is usually 2\u20133 eggs, varying from 1\u20134 overall.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" /> The second egg is typically laid within 24 hours of the first. Eggs are approximately 20 x 15&nbsp;cm, weighing 2.45g; oval, smooth, finely grained and may be slightly glossy. Colour varies from white to yellowish, light red or pink. Markings may vary from uniform reddish freckles to purplish or dark reddish-brown spots. Marks are sometimes in greater frequency at the large end. Eggs laid late in season tend to be lighter, and those from inland populations tend to be white with fewer markings.\n\nDetails about incubation duties are unknown, although they are thought to be performed only by the female. Eggs are incubated for 10\u201314 days before hatching. Both sexes feed offspring with females brooding, leaving only when the male arrives to feed chicks. Both parents remove faecal sacs and eggshell fragments. Parents undertake distraction displays when predators approach nests, mainly in the final days before nestlings fledge. Fledging occurs 12\u201313 days after hatching and juveniles are fed for two or more weeks after leaving nest.\n\nWhite-plumed honeyeaters are parasitised by [[Pallid cuckoo|pallid]] and [[Fan-tailed cuckoo|fan-tailed]] cuckoos, as well as [[Horsfield's bronze-cuckoo|Horsfield's]]  and [[Shining bronze-cuckoo|shining]] bronze-cuckoos.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" />\n\n==Conservation status==\n\nThe white-plumed honeyeater is considered by the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature]] (IUCN) to be of [[least concern]] for conservation.<ref name=\"IUCN\" />\n\n===Threats===\n\nExotic vertebrate predators, such as cats and dogs, are a direct threat to white-plumed honeyeater populations.<ref name=\"HANZAB\" />\nLoss of trees from watercourses will impact a population; however, they are able to adapt to suburban environments, especially where native gardens are present.\n\n===Climate effects===\n\nThe white-plumed honeyeater body-size has been observed to change over recent decades, with individuals becoming smaller in extended drought, but showing an overall trend towards larger body-size since the 1960s.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Gardner|first1=Janet L. |last2=Amano |first2=Tatsuya |last3=Mackey|first3=Brendan G.|last4=Sutherland|first4=William J. |last5=Clayton |first5=Mark |last6=Peters |first6=Anne |title=Dynamic size responses to climate change: prevailing effects of rising temperature drive long-term body size increases in a semi-arid passerine|journal=Global Change Biology|date=2014|volume=2|issue=7|pages=2062\u20132075|doi=10.1111/gcb.12507}}</ref> This is correlated with increasing temperatures in the regions surveyed, with body size increasing by 0.064% per year.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Gardner|first1=Janet L.|last2=Amano|first2=Tatsuya|last3=Backwell|first3=Patrica R.Y. |last4=Ikin |first4=Karen |last5=Sutherland |first5=William J.|last6=Peters|first6=Anne|title=Temporal patterns of avian body size reflect linear size responses to broadscale environmental change over the last 50 years|journal=Journal of Avian Biology|date=2014|volume=45|issue=6|pages=529\u2013535 |doi=10.1111/jav.00431}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Commons|Lichenostomus penicillatus}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.xeno-canto.org/species/Ptilotula-penicillata White plumed honeyeater sound recordings at Xeno Canto] \n*[http://bie.ala.org.au/species/urn:lsid:biodiversity.org.au:afd.taxon:a98f7d77-5d5b-48a0-a38f-a4ceaadb5d89 Distribution information at Atlas of Living Australia]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q27075261}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:honeyeater, white-plumed}}\n[[Category:Ptilotula|white-plumed honeyeater]]\n[[Category:Endemic birds of Australia]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1837|white-plumed honeyeater]]\n", "name_user": "Rogermccart", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReproduction:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White-plumed_honeyeater"}
{"title_page": "Ju-Jitsu International Federation", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{notability|Sports|date=September 2013}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2013}}\n{{update|date=May 2012}}}}\n{{Infobox martial art school\n| logo               = \n| logocaption        = \n| logosize           = \n| image              = \n| imagecaption       = \n| imagesize          = \n| name               = Ju-Jitsu International Federation\n| aka                = JJIF\n| date founded       = 1977 (as EJJF)\n| country            = \n| founder            = \n| head               = \n| arts               =  [[Ju-Jitsu|Modern Ju-Jitsu]]\n| ancestor_arts      =  [[Ju-Jitsu]]\n| descendant_arts    = \n| ancestor schools   = \n| descendant schools = \n| notable pract      = \n| website            = http://www.jjif.org/\n}}\n\nThe '''Ju-Jitsu International Federation''' ('''JJIF''') is an international sport federation founded in 1998 after the expansion of the ''European Ju-Jitsu Federation'' (EJJF) for the propagation of the modern competitive sports version of [[Jujitsu]], also known as ''Sport Ju-Jitsu''.\n\nAs a member of the [[General Association of International Sport Federations]] ([[GAISF]]) and the [[International World Games Association]] (IWGA), the JJIF represents Sports Ju-Jitsu worldwide. The JJIF is currently the only Jujutsu/Ju-Jitsu organization recognized by the GAISF and IWGA; Ju-Jitsu under JJIF rules is a part of the [[World Games]]<ref>[http://www.kjjbwf.org/ Korea Jujitsu Belt Wrestling Federation website]</ref> and [[World Combat Games]].<ref>http://www.worldcombatgames.com/en/sports/17/Ju-Jitsu</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe Federation commenced as a coalition of three countries' associations. In 1977, delegates form Germany, Italy and Sweden founded the European Ju-Jitsu Federation (EJJF). As the number of member Nations increased, in and out of Europe, in 1987 the Federation changed its name to International Ju-Jitsu Federation (IJJF) and the original European nucleus of the Federation became the first Continental Union (EJJU) of the IJJF.  Following a series of changes of its Statutes and a change to its membership structure, in 1998, the IJJF decided to change its name to the Ju-Jitsu International Federation (JJIF).<ref>[http://www.jjifweb.com/html/ju-jitsu.html What is Ju-jitsu], JJIF website]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090529123759/http://www.jjifweb.com/html/ju-jitsu.html |date=29 May 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s the IJJF became a provisional member of the [[SportAccord|General Association of International Sport Federations]] (GAISF), member of [[International World Games Association]] (IWGA \u2013 part of the Olympic Movement together with the IOC) and affiliated to the Sport for All Federation (FISpT). During the 1998 GAISF Congress the JJIF obtained full membership status.\n\nJu-Jitsu under JJIF rules has been an event at the [[World Games]] since the [[1997 World Games]] in Lahti, Finland.\n\n== Traditional Jujutsu and Sport Ju-Jitsu ==\n\nDifferent schools ([[ry\u016b (school)|ry\u016b]]) have been teaching traditional Jujutsu in Japan since the 15th century. The JJIF is not a governing body for any of these schools of traditional Japanese jujutsu\u2014the JJIF does not exercise authority over traditional Japanese Jujutsu [[Koryu]] styles, which are often instead headed by leaders who claim leadership from unbroken lineages of transmissions from different Japanese ry\u016b, some of them hundreds of years old.\n\nRather, the JJIF was founded as an international federation solely for governing Sport Ju-Jitsu, a competitive sport derived from traditional jujutsu.\n\n== Rules of Sport Ju-Jitsu ==\n\nJJIF currently regulates three different types of competitions at the international level: the ''Duo system''', ''Fighting system'' and ''Ne Waza''.<ref>The official rules can be found at the [http://www.jjif-referees.com/ JJIF-Referees website.]</ref>\n\n===Duo===\nThe former is a discipline in which a pair of Jutsukas (Ju-Jitsu athlete) from the same team show possible self-defence techniques against a series of 12 attacks, randomly called by the mat referee from the 20 codified attacks to cover the following typologies: grip attack (or strangulation), embrace attack (or necklock), hit attack (punch or kick) and armed attack (stick or knife).\n\nThe Duo system has three competition categories: male, female or mixed, and the athletes are judged for their speed, accuracy, control and realism. It is arguably the most spectacular form of Ju-jitsu competition and it requires great technical preparation, synchronicity and elevated athletic qualities.\n\n===Fighting===\nWith a different approach, the Fighting System is articulated in a one-on-one competition between athletes. The system is divided in several categories according to weight and sex\n\n(Male categories: -55&nbsp;kg, \u221262&nbsp;kg, \u221269&nbsp;kg, \u221277&nbsp;kg, \u221285&nbsp;kg, \u221294&nbsp;kg, +94&nbsp;kg; Female categories \u221248&nbsp;kg, \u221255&nbsp;kg, \u221262&nbsp;kg, \u221270&nbsp;kg, +70&nbsp;kg).\n\nThe actual competition is divided in three phases (Parts): Part I sees the jutsukas involved in distance combat (controlled attacks with arms and legs and atemis of various nature \u2013 punches, strikes and kicks). Once a grab has been made the Fight enters Part II and hits are no longer allowed.\n\nThe jutsukas try to bring one another down with various throwing techniques (and points are given according to how \"clean\" and effective the action was). Also \u2013 despite being uncommon \u2013 submission techniques as controlled strangulations and locks are allowed in part II.\n\nOnce down on the tatamis (mats) the match enters its Part III. Here points are given for immobilisation techniques, controlled strangulations or levers on body joints that bring the opponent to yield.\n\nThe winner is the Jutsuka who has accumulated most points during the fight. Automatic victory is assigned to the Jutsuka who gets an \"Ippon\" (clean action, full points) in all three Parts. This type of competition requires timing, agility, strength and endurance.\n\n===Ne-Waza===\nNe-Waza (ground technique) is one of the main Jujitsu (and Judo) bases. The fight of two opponents starts standing. Punches and kicks are not allowed. After starting the fight the referee interrupts only in critical moments, so normally the main part of the fight takes place on the ground. It is the goal to win by submission with a lock on the joints or strangulation. During the time of 6 minutes it is possible to gain points for throws, take-downs, controlling positions and actions to gain an advantage in the fight. The Ne-Waza Ju-Jitsu is extremely tactical and sometimes described as the chess game of martial arts. This ruleset is similar to [[Brazilian jiu-jitsu]] rules.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Weight categories in JJIF ne-waza-system\n|-\n! age !! sex !! colspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | weight categories\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Cadets (U17) || male || \u221255&nbsp;kg || \u221260&nbsp;kg || \u221266&nbsp;kg || \u221273&nbsp;kg || \u221281&nbsp;kg || \u221290&nbsp;kg || +90&nbsp;kg\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | female || \u221244&nbsp;kg || \u221248&nbsp;kg || \u221252&nbsp;kg || \u221257&nbsp;kg || \u221263&nbsp;kg || \u221270&nbsp;kg || +70&nbsp;kg\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Juniors (U20) <br /> Seniors || \u221248&nbsp;kg || \u221252&nbsp;kg || \u221257&nbsp;kg || \u221263&nbsp;kg || \u221270&nbsp;kg || \u221278&nbsp;kg || +78&nbsp;kg\n|-\n| male || \u221260&nbsp;kg || \u221266&nbsp;kg || \u221273&nbsp;kg || \u221281&nbsp;kg || \u221290&nbsp;kg || \u2212100&nbsp;kg || +100&nbsp;kg\n|}\n\nThe contest duration is 4 minutes for cadets, 6 minutes for juniors and seniors (<=35 years) and 5 minutes for competitors from 36 years onwards.\n\n== Sport Ju-Jitsu and the Olympic Movement ==\n\nThe JJIF is a member of [[GAISF]] and [[IWGA]], and both organizations are in close cooperation with the [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC). The organisation is striving to establish Sports Ju-Jitsu as an Olympic event in the future.<ref>[http://www.usjujitsu.net/news/article1.html Traditional Ju-Jitsu shines bright as gold at the Sixth World Games], Grappling Magazine, March 2002</ref>\n\n{{portal|Martial arts}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.usjjo.org/ United Society of JuJitsu Organizations - Official Website]\n* [http://www.jjif.org/ JJIF Official Website]\n* [http://jjif-referees.com/ JJIF Referees Official Website]\n* [http://jujitsu.or.kr Official Member of JJIF , Vice President of JJAU - Korea Ju-Jitsu Association - KJJA]\n\n\n{{International Sports Federations}}\n\n[[Category:Jujutsu organizations]]\n[[Category:International sports organizations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2014}}\n{{multiple issues|\n{{notability|Sports|date=September 2013}}\n{{refimprove|date=September 2013}}\n{{update|date=May 2012}}}}\n{{Infobox martial art school\n| logo               = \n| logocaption        = \n| logosize           = \n| image              = \n| imagecaption       = \n| imagesize          = \n| name               = Ju-Jitsu International Federation\n| aka                = JJIF\n| date founded       = 1977 (as EJJF)\n| country            = \n| founder            = \n| head               = \n| arts               =  [[Ju-Jitsu|Modern Ju-Jitsu]]\n| ancestor_arts      =  [[Ju-Jitsu]]\n| descendant_arts    = \n| ancestor schools   = \n| descendant schools = \n| notable pract      = \n| website            = http://www.jjif.info/\n}}\n\nThe '''Ju-Jitsu International Federation''' ('''JJIF''') is an international sport federation founded in 1998 after the expansion of the ''European Ju-Jitsu Federation'' (EJJF) for the propagation of the modern competitive sports version of [[Jujitsu]], also known as ''Sport Ju-Jitsu''.\n\nAs a member of the [[General Association of International Sport Federations]] ([[GAISF]]) and the [[International World Games Association]] (IWGA), the JJIF represents Sports Ju-Jitsu worldwide. The JJIF is currently the only Jujutsu/Ju-Jitsu organization recognized by the GAISF and IWGA; Ju-Jitsu under JJIF rules is a part of the [[World Games]]<ref>[http://www.kjjbwf.org/ Korea Jujitsu Belt Wrestling Federation website]</ref> and [[World Combat Games]].<ref>http://www.worldcombatgames.com/en/sports/17/Ju-Jitsu</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe Federation commenced as a coalition of three countries' associations. In 1977, delegates form Germany, Italy and Sweden founded the European Ju-Jitsu Federation (EJJF). As the number of member Nations increased, in and out of Europe, in 1987 the Federation changed its name to International Ju-Jitsu Federation (IJJF) and the original European nucleus of the Federation became the first Continental Union (EJJU) of the IJJF.  Following a series of changes of its Statutes and a change to its membership structure, in 1998, the IJJF decided to change its name to the Ju-Jitsu International Federation (JJIF).<ref>[http://www.jjifweb.com/html/ju-jitsu.html What is Ju-jitsu], JJIF website]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090529123759/http://www.jjifweb.com/html/ju-jitsu.html |date=29 May 2009 }}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s the IJJF became a provisional member of the [[SportAccord|General Association of International Sport Federations]] (GAISF), member of [[International World Games Association]] (IWGA \u2013 part of the Olympic Movement together with the IOC) and affiliated to the Sport for All Federation (FISpT). During the 1998 GAISF Congress the JJIF obtained full membership status.\n\nJu-Jitsu under JJIF rules has been an event at the [[World Games]] since the [[1997 World Games]] in Lahti, Finland.\n\n== Traditional Jujutsu and Sport Ju-Jitsu ==\n\nDifferent schools ([[ry\u016b (school)|ry\u016b]]) have been teaching traditional Jujutsu in Japan since the 15th century. The JJIF is not a governing body for any of these schools of traditional Japanese jujutsu\u2014the JJIF does not exercise authority over traditional Japanese Jujutsu [[Koryu]] styles, which are often instead headed by leaders who claim leadership from unbroken lineages of transmissions from different Japanese ry\u016b, some of them hundreds of years old.\n\nRather, the JJIF was founded as an international federation solely for governing Sport Ju-Jitsu, a competitive sport derived from traditional jujutsu.\n\n== Rules of Sport Ju-Jitsu ==\n\nJJIF currently regulates three different types of competitions at the international level: the ''Duo system''', ''Fighting system'' and ''Ne Waza''.<ref>The official rules can be found at the [http://www.jjif-referees.com/ JJIF-Referees website.]</ref>\n\n===Duo===\nThe former is a discipline in which a pair of Jutsukas (Ju-Jitsu athlete) from the same team show possible self-defence techniques against a series of 12 attacks, randomly called by the mat referee from the 20 codified attacks to cover the following typologies: grip attack (or strangulation), embrace attack (or necklock), hit attack (punch or kick) and armed attack (stick or knife).\n\nThe Duo system has three competition categories: male, female or mixed, and the athletes are judged for their speed, accuracy, control and realism. It is arguably the most spectacular form of Ju-jitsu competition and it requires great technical preparation, synchronicity and elevated athletic qualities.\n\n===Fighting===\nWith a different approach, the Fighting System is articulated in a one-on-one competition between athletes. The system is divided in several categories according to weight and sex\n\n(Male categories: -55&nbsp;kg, \u221262&nbsp;kg, \u221269&nbsp;kg, \u221277&nbsp;kg, \u221285&nbsp;kg, \u221294&nbsp;kg, +94&nbsp;kg; Female categories \u221248&nbsp;kg, \u221255&nbsp;kg, \u221262&nbsp;kg, \u221270&nbsp;kg, +70&nbsp;kg).\n\nThe actual competition is divided in three phases (Parts): Part I sees the jutsukas involved in distance combat (controlled attacks with arms and legs and atemis of various nature \u2013 punches, strikes and kicks). Once a grab has been made the Fight enters Part II and hits are no longer allowed.\n\nThe jutsukas try to bring one another down with various throwing techniques (and points are given according to how \"clean\" and effective the action was). Also \u2013 despite being uncommon \u2013 submission techniques as controlled strangulations and locks are allowed in part II.\n\nOnce down on the tatamis (mats) the match enters its Part III. Here points are given for immobilisation techniques, controlled strangulations or levers on body joints that bring the opponent to yield.\n\nThe winner is the Jutsuka who has accumulated most points during the fight. Automatic victory is assigned to the Jutsuka who gets an \"Ippon\" (clean action, full points) in all three Parts. This type of competition requires timing, agility, strength and endurance.\n\n===Ne-Waza===\nNe-Waza (ground technique) is one of the main Jujitsu (and Judo) bases. The fight of two opponents starts standing. Punches and kicks are not allowed. After starting the fight the referee interrupts only in critical moments, so normally the main part of the fight takes place on the ground. It is the goal to win by submission with a lock on the joints or strangulation. During the time of 6 minutes it is possible to gain points for throws, take-downs, controlling positions and actions to gain an advantage in the fight. The Ne-Waza Ju-Jitsu is extremely tactical and sometimes described as the chess game of martial arts. This ruleset is similar to [[Brazilian jiu-jitsu]] rules.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+ Weight categories in JJIF ne-waza-system\n|-\n! age !! sex !! colspan=\"7\" style=\"text-align: center;\" | weight categories\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Cadets (U17) || male || \u221255&nbsp;kg || \u221260&nbsp;kg || \u221266&nbsp;kg || \u221273&nbsp;kg || \u221281&nbsp;kg || \u221290&nbsp;kg || +90&nbsp;kg\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | female || \u221244&nbsp;kg || \u221248&nbsp;kg || \u221252&nbsp;kg || \u221257&nbsp;kg || \u221263&nbsp;kg || \u221270&nbsp;kg || +70&nbsp;kg\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Juniors (U20) <br /> Seniors || \u221248&nbsp;kg || \u221252&nbsp;kg || \u221257&nbsp;kg || \u221263&nbsp;kg || \u221270&nbsp;kg || \u221278&nbsp;kg || +78&nbsp;kg\n|-\n| male || \u221260&nbsp;kg || \u221266&nbsp;kg || \u221273&nbsp;kg || \u221281&nbsp;kg || \u221290&nbsp;kg || \u2212100&nbsp;kg || +100&nbsp;kg\n|}\n\nThe contest duration is 4 minutes for cadets, 6 minutes for juniors and seniors (<=35 years) and 5 minutes for competitors from 36 years onwards.\n\n== Sport Ju-Jitsu and the Olympic Movement ==\n\nThe JJIF is a member of [[GAISF]] and [[IWGA]], and both organizations are in close cooperation with the [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC). The organisation is striving to establish Sports Ju-Jitsu as an Olympic event in the future.<ref>[http://www.usjujitsu.net/news/article1.html Traditional Ju-Jitsu shines bright as gold at the Sixth World Games], Grappling Magazine, March 2002</ref>\n\n{{portal|Martial arts}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.usjjo.org/ United Society of JuJitsu Organizations - Official Website]\n* [http://www.jjif.info/ JJIF Official Website]\n* [http://jjif-referees.com/ JJIF Referees Official Website]\n* [http://jujitsu.or.kr Official Member of JJIF , Vice President of JJAU - Korea Ju-Jitsu Association - KJJA]\n\n\n{{International Sports Federations}}\n\n[[Category:Jujutsu organizations]]\n[[Category:International sports organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Prikryl", "label": "safe", "comment": "link update_", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ju-Jitsu_International_Federation"}
{"title_page": "General debate of the sixty-fourth session of the United Nations General Assembly", "text_new": "{{Infobox summit meeting\n| name         = General Debate of the sixty-fourth session of the United Nations General Assembly\n| other_titles = \n| logo         = \n| logo_size    = \n| logo_alt     = \n| image        = UN General Assembly hall.jpg\n| alt          = \n| caption      = General Assembly hall at United Nations Headquarters, New York City\n| country      = {{flag|United Nations}}\n| date         = 23 \u2013 29 September 2009\n| motto        =\n| venues       = [[United Nations Headquarters]]\n| cities       = [[New York City]], United States\n| participants = [[Member states of the United Nations|United Nations Member States]]\n| president    = [[Ali Abdussalam Treki]]\n| follows      = [[General debate of the sixty-third session of the United Nations General Assembly|63rd]]\n| precedes     = [[General debate of the sixty-fifth session of the United Nations General Assembly|65th]]\n| website      = {{URL|https://www.un.org/en/ga/64/}}\n| keypoints    = \n| compactnav   = yes\n}}\n\nThe '''General Debate of the sixty-fourth session of the United Nations General Assembly''' opened on 23 September 2009 and ran until 29 September. Leaders from a number of member states addressed the General Assembly.\n\n== Organisation ==\nThe order of speakers is given first to Member States, then Observer States and supranational bodies. Speakers are put on a speaking list in the order of their request, with special consideration for ministers and other government officials of similar or higher rank. According to the rules in place for the General Debate, the statements should be in one of the United Nations official languages of [[Arabic]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], [[English language|English]], [[French language|French]], [[Russian language|Russian]] or [[Spanish language|Spanish]], and will be translated by the [[United Nations translators]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thenational.ae/world/the-americas/how-is-the-order-of-speakers-at-the-un-general-assembly-decided-1.772638 |title=How is the order of speakers at the UN General Assembly decided? |author=Capel, Charles |date=22 September 2018 |website=The National |publisher=[[The National (Abu Dhabi)|The National]] |access-date=15 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe theme for the 64th Session was chosen by President [[Ali Abdussalam Treki]] as: \"Effective responses to global crises: strengthening multilateralism and dialogue among civilizations for international peace, security and development.\"<ref name=\"64th Session\">{{cite web |url=https://www.un.org/en/ga/64/ |title=64th session |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |website=General Assembly of the United Nations |publisher=United Nations |access-date=13 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Speaking schedule ==\n=== 23 September ===\n'''Morning session''' <ref name=\"GEN DEBATE\">{{cite web |url=https://gadebate.un.org/en/sessions-archive/64 |title=General Debate 64th Session: 23 September 2009 to 29 September 2009 |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=n.d. |website=General Assembly of the United Nations |publisher=United Nations |access-date=14 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{UN doc |docid=A/64/PV.3 |body=A |session=64 |type=Official record |document_number=PV.3 |title=General Assembly Sixty-fourth session: 3rd plenary meeting, Wednesday, 23 September 2009, 9 a.m. New York |date= 23 September 2009 |accessdate=15 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n* {{Flag|United Nations}} \u2013 Secretary-General [[Ban Ki-moon]] (Report of the Secretary-General on the work of the\nOrganization)\n* {{Flag|United Nations}} \u2013 President of the 64th session of the General Assembly [[Ali Abdussalam Treki]] (Opening)\n* {{Flag|Brazil}} \u2013 President [[Luiz In\u00e1cio Lula da Silva]]\n* {{Flag|United States}} \u2013 President [[Barack Obama]]\n* {{Flag|Libya|1977}} \u2013 Leader of the Revolution [[Muammar Gaddafi|Colonel Muammar Al-Qadhafi]]\n* {{Fla